The group is part of the Institute of Logic and Computation of the Faculty of Informatics at TU Wien , Vienna, Austria The group s research is concerned with the development and analysis of efficient algorithms for hard computational problems arising in a wide range of practical applications, as well as the establishment of theoretical limits of algorithmic The Algorithms and Complexity Group is committed to teach undergraduate and graduate courses in Computer Science, as well as to supervise Bachelor, Masters and Doctoral The group is located in a department building of TU Wien, in Vienna s Fourth District, close to Karlsplatz and the city centre, see here how to reach us . Acting Office - Acting Office is all that your practice Its an integrated software platform that helps you with practice management, tax & accounts, payroll Contact Organise your practice with Acting Office Acting Office is a software platform that helps accountants with a practice management It offers a host of features such as email integration, phone integration, task management, timesheets, deadline reminders, canned messages, data storage All these features ensure seamless management of all client related tasks and The best part is that, being , it can be accessed from anywhere providing added Email integration Allows you to receive and send emails directly from the Acting Office app (instead of gmail outlook). Your client communication history gets organised like never before with the automatic mapping of the emails to the particular Phone integration Ensures that you have a record of each incoming outgoing call for every You can add a summary note to each call, so that you don t need to listen the recording for any important matter that was discussed, which significantly enhances the efficiency of team Task management Helps you set up tasks (recurring or standalone) for and efficient handling of clients You can choose the priority level for each task and they will be presented accordingly on your Timesheets Performance analysis is a very important element for large practices with multiple staff members, many times based in different geographical Our timesheet feature not only lets your staff feed in details of the work they ve done, but it also smartly finds out their actual devotion of work on a specific task through Deadline reminders A missed deadline is an accountant s worst nightmare, but you don t need to worry about this as Acting Office helps you receive the deadline reminders exactly as per your customised needs and always keeps you on top of the filing Canned messages A lot of accountant emails look the same for example, a quote for your services, a confirmation email after filing the accounts, a checklist of the information that you need from a We understand this completely and hence, offer you an option to customise your own canned messages for each of such actions and then use them to save time whilst ensuring accuracy attaining the much needed peace of For more information, email us at <U+00A9> Copyright Acting Office - All Rights Reserved Privacy Policy Terms and Conditions

AGPA <U+0096> Augmented field Geology and Geophysics for Planetary Analogues Skip to content AGPA Augmented field Geology and Geophysics for Planetary Analogues Menu Home Team Blog Privacy Scroll down to content Home A ugmented field G eology and G eophysics for P lanetary A nalogues Why AGPA? The AGPA set of experiments project aims at integrating training and data collection with geophysical and remote sensing methods with analogue field geology procedures Training in basic geoscience as well as using specialised geophysical equipment allowed for an impressive scientific return for the relatively limited set of Apollo mission to the Future exploration can count on much more advanced techniques and experiments, such as laser scanning: Basic geophysical data collection can be of great importance for contextualising geological information collected by human or robotic explorers as well as for capturing geological information hidden to regular geological reconnaissance, and provide AGPA experiments remote sensing mapping: will perform a photogrammetric survey of the Site A (Tinguiat<f3>n) for acquisition of imagery, GPS and creation of topographic Gathered imaging and mapping data will be integrated with additional datasets to highlight methods and techniques to study planetary analogue Geologic, morphologic and morphometric studies based on the topography and additional ancillary collected datasets are Data will be widely made Geoelectrical probing of lava tubes from the surface: The Electrical Resistivity Tomography (ERT) will allow identifying and characterizing lava tubes and providing resistivity models of the Site D & E around the Corona Two configurations will be Alternatively, one long profile might be replaced by a more detailed investigation involving a m x m sized grid, which would represent a survey focused on a small size target (small lava tube) and would provide a resistivity Laser scanning from inside lava tubes: will perform a mapping of the Corona lava tube (PANGAEA-X Site C) with (LiDAR) as well as NIR (thermal) imaging, allowing to create a detailed model of this lava The experiment is going to test different mobile methods for generating a model of the lava tube and to evaluate the models against ground truth data, providing accurate reconstruction of the subsurface morphology and structure, matched with surface geology and subsurface geophysical Passive seismic monitoring: will perform seismic measurements in the area of the sites, including activity associated to Canary Islands volcanoes as well as from the wider area encompassing the ridge and the plate You can follow AGPA and ESA PANGEA efficiency of analog with the precision control of digital Breakthrough Computing Performance We are accelerating technology beyond the limits of Moore s Law Hybrid Computing century industrial design icons Charles and Ray Eames noted that measuring the weight of honey on a gradual scale is analog whereas counting sugar cubes in discrete units is They likened analog to broad jump where manifestations of performance are measured along a continuous And they likened digital to high jump where performance is evaluated against a preset At that time, analog and digital had already brought about two seperate approaches to electronic Today, analog is a , yet underutilized computing paradigm next to the ubiquitous digital and the infant quantum Digital computing, well suited for algorithmic symbol processing in discrete steps, is less suited to model continuous relationships Today s urgent challenges in new energy research, public health, economic modelling and elsewhere, however, require precisely the modelling of continuous Analog computing is ideally suited to address these challenges with unparalleled speed and Once seen as an alternative to digital, analog can complement digital in hybrid This offers a path to accelerate computing beyond the impending end of Moore s To this day, however, the enormous potential of hybrid computing remains largely At anabrid, we are designing an analog computer Its integration into digital computers will yield powerful, and hybrids of the two computational Incorporating thousands of analog computing elements operated at scale under digital control, anabrid s analog computer will complement digital technology <U+0096> combining the benefits of both to compute more, faster, and Application Potential The analog computer opens the door to another computing paradigm for the The principles of its operations and of its implementation in silicon are Its potential to support and enhance digital computation is To illustrate this potential, we divide it into eight segments using three distinctions: User experience: Users may be aware of using an analog computer ( engaged ) or they may be unaware of it ( hidden ). Scale: A given application may harness a few dozen analog computing elements ( small scale) or vastly more analog computing elements can be deployed ( large scale). Purpose: An analog computer may be applied with a fixed configuration ( special purpose) or its users may be able to its programming ( general purpose). - Open Distributed Toggle navigation Home The Mission How it Works FAQ Get Involved Open Distributed s mission is to bring together and interconnect multiple narrow agents to create an Open Distributed Join the Mission Discussion Group GitHub The Mission Build the first Open Source Distributed AI We are in the very early staging of figuring out how to build a distributed Artificial Intelligence (A.I.) where a multitude of narrow agents with specialised skills can be brought toghether to build a more general intelligent How it works Well ... we haven t figured out that part yet, that s why we need But the main idea is this: 1 Create an AI agent with narrow skills which can be discovered by other AI agents in the network Most AI agents these days have a focused narrow For example you can make an AI agent that detects emotions in a video but most likely is not That s OK, you can focus on improving those specific skills and you can still benefit from a wide variety of other skills provided AI agents in the network by joining to the 2 Create Standards for AI Agent Skill Discoverability Create well defined standards and interfaces for boarcasting and discovering the type of skills and AI agent 3 Create an AI Agent Trust Service A trust system must be created to review the quality of AI agents provided in the Frequently Asked Questions How do I join? You can join by participaing on discussion we have on ark-ai . Also you can contibute code on ark-ai . How much work has been done on this project so far? The project is at the very beginnings and currenly we are currently defining the main The next phase is to figure out what would be the best course of action to make this idea an Ready? Genome Sciences Centre Skip to main content Utility For Patients - Find a Clinical Trial Canada s Michael Smith Genome Sciences Centre Excellence in genomics, proteomics and bioinformatics for precision About Us Canada s Michael Smith Genome Sciences Centre From Nobel Our Story Canada s Michael Smith Genome Sciences Centre Developing new strategies to prevent, diagnose and treat cancers and other Clinical Services Canada s Michael Smith Genome Sciences Centre Expert assistance with experimental design and biotechnology Collaborative Services Canada s Michael Smith Genome Sciences Centre Harnessing genome sequencing and analytical Technology Platform Canada s Michael Smith Genome Sciences Centre Enabling new ways to process, analyze and visualize genomic Software Resources Canada s Michael Smith Genome Sciences Centre Realizing the social and economic benefits of genome Research Projects Developing and deploying genomics technologies in support of cancer and life sciences Canada s Michael Smith Genome Sciences Centre (GSC) at BC Cancer is an international leader in genomics, proteomics and bioinformatics for precision By developing and deploying genome sequencing, computational and analytical technology, we are creating novel strategies to prevent and diagnose cancers and other diseases, uncovering new therapeutic targets and helping the world realize the social and economic benefits of genome Technology Platform The GSC is available to support your We guide experimental design, facilitate the processing of complex biological samples and provide numerous sequencing and bioinformatic services with the aim of making genomics accessible to the international scientific Explore our technology platforms and services , and if you have questions or would like to collaborate please fill out our contact form or speak directly with one of our platform leaders . The GSC is ISO27001 certified for information security Scientific Research The faculty members at the GSC have a diverse range of expertise in genomics, bioinformatics, proteomics, epigenomics, immunogenetics, cancer biology, computer science and software development . Together, we apply our knowledge to advance the global understanding of cancer and other diseases with an ultimate aim toward improving human health through disease prevention, the development of novel diagnostic strategies and by uncovering new therapeutic approaches, all the while helping the world to realize the social and economic benefits of genome research . Clinical Programs The GSC is unique in that it fosters close collaborations between scientists and clinicians, allowing for an unencumbered focus on direct translational Through the Personalized OncoGenomics (POG) program , the GSC deploys whole genome and transcriptome sequencing to inform therapeutic and management strategies for cancer patients in real The GSC is also certified by the College of American Pathologists (CAP) and the Diagnostic Accreditation Program (DAP) to perform clinical genomic panel Questions? BitLet - Bittorrent applet | Alessandro Bahgat Search Home Blog Projects Experience Contact Me BitLet - Bittorrent Applet BitLet - Bittorrent applet Oct , Code In the summer of , shortly after launching Novlet , Daniele and I still had time to spare and were looking for something new to Sure enough, within a short period, Daniele came up with the idea that would soon become BitLet: a BitTorrent client that could run in a browser without requiring users to install anything on their Back then, browsers had very limited capabilities: AJAX had been recently introduced (in ), web applications were moving from static pages to dynamic client UIs but no browser could do things like opening sockets and writing files locally, central requirements for a peer to peer file sharing We found a solution in an unlikely piece of technology: Java Despite Java<U+0092>s success as a programming language, applets had never been that popular among casual While a good idea in principle (small applications that could be downloaded and launched from web pages), the concept never got traction beyond a few One of the main reasons is that Java applets didn<U+0092>t look that Given the need to run across multiple platforms (Windows, Linux, Mac), applets used their own window toolkit for rendering interfaces, which led to UIs that always looked quite different from what users were expecting most of the What made BitLet possible, however, was the idea that we could have the applet implement the BitTorrent protocol while relying only on the browser for its The interface we had in mind was very simple, centered around a streamlined download We had a first version shortly after, an applet with no Java UI that would use JavaScript to communicate with the hosting browser to handle events and drive page We built a very simple website around it and published Within days, BitLet took People loved the simplicity and the ability to use BitTorrent anywhere, without needing to install any client One of the very first articles featuring BitLet stated: Very useful if you want to share a torrent with your BitTorrent illiterate friends, or if you<U+0092>re on a computer that doesn<U+0092>t have a BitTorrent client [<U+0085>] I<U+0092>ve tried it with a couple of torrents and it seems to be working quite well, just enter the url of the file and you<U+0092>re good to The download speeds are decent and doesn<U+0092>t require any configuration, so it<U+0092>s pretty much As user took notice, a few prominent file sharing sites did too, and embedded links to BitLet on their download We kept adding features, introduced the option to stream music and video as they were being downloaded, added UPnP support to open ports on home routers for faster transfer speeds, wrote a Chrome extension to make BitLet the default download option for We had a great time working on this, it<U+0092>s been a great side project that was also very interesting Years later, applets became less and less popular, with several browsers dropping support for the Java plugin that allowed running applets, which led Sun to officially deprecate the technology in That signaled the end of an era for us: BitLet was considerably harder to use for people and the initial value of simplicity we built the applet around We turned off in and open sourced parts of the infrastructure: bitlet <U+0096> BitLet<U+0092>s BitTorrent core code weupnp <U+0096> lightweight library implementing UPnP BitLet4Chrome <U+0096> Chrome extension p2p Bittorrent web Java Alessandro Bahgat Software Engineer & Manager I am an engineer and manager of engineers , I sometimes play with side projects and write about my experiences in my spare Liked this? You can sign up here to be notified of new Low frequency, no Email address Subscribe Previous Novlet Next Java Generalized Suffix Tree Related Novlet Posts Bittorrent video streaming on Bitlet We recently updated to add support for video streaming via The applet allows you to watch videos while you are downloading them and doesn<U+0092>t require the installation of any third party application, except for May 6, 1 min read Web <U+00A9> <U+00B7> Powered by the Academic theme for Hugo . targeting construction areas where, from our industry experience, we believe blockchain can help to improve These areas include, project progress tracking, health & safety management and design These solutions can be configured to meet the specific needs and problems of your Through working alongside our clients to implement blockchain solutions that solve real world construction problems we aim Read More about Calibro is a multidisciplinary design studio established in and based in Milan, We are interested in exploring new pathways at the intersection between design, data visualization and We use the potential of data visualization and information design to provide innovative and engaging visual tools for clients, users and researchers, embracing complexity and In the past few years we have been involved in research, consulting and teaching activities for several public and private For new collaborations and projects contact us at Our areas of expertise include: Data Visualization Front End Development Web scraping Coding Data refining User Experience Information Design Mapping App Development Design Research Visualizing Geographical Information Graphic Design Web Design Job positions Full stack developer We are looking for a motivated full stack developer able to work in a team and follow the development of You should have an experience in development (Python, ), database management (SQL-like DBs, MongoDB) and a good knowledge of You will work with the most common web technologies, frameworks (React, ) and libraries (d3.js, Bootstrap). Collaborators and Interns We are a small studio and we like We always look for professionals that can join our team for specific projects or students and recent graduates that want to develop their skills in the field of data visualization, UX UI or web If you are freelancer in UX UI design, visual design, web development, data science or an independent researcher and you look for interesting projects, drop us a people Matteo Azzi Giorgio Uboldi office Piazza Prealpi 3, Milano - ITALY social You can find us on Twitter & Facebook & Medium & Github & Behance & Telegram . selected clients Anthropocene Observatory, Arup, Code for Africa, Data4Change, ENSCI Les Ateliers, Hogeschool van Amsterdam, Luxembourg Centre for Contemporary and Digital History (C<U+00B2>DH), Mozilla Foundation, PARK Associati, Sciences Po M<e9>dialab, The Outpost Magazine, University of Amsterdam, Visualizing Impact, WIRED Italy, ZKM Karlsruhe, and dotdotdot details VAT number: IT09323480963 Headquarter: Piazza Prealpi, 3 - Milano about

<U+FEFF> cmail: Overview cmail Internet mail processing suite with SQLite backend cmail is an implementation of multiple protocols to fulfill most, if not all functions commonly expected in internet message exchange - commonly known as "mail server". Architecturally, cmail is split into several modules which interface through a central SQLite database (the master database ). For most modules, a administration tool is SMTP server (Accept incoming originated mails) POP server (Access mailboxes via POP) IMAP server (Access mailboxes via IMAP) SMTP client (Deliver outgoing mails to remote servers) HTTP API to the master database Web mailer interface HTTP Administration interface Manage cmail users Administration of inbound mail paths Administration of outbound mail handling Control access to the POP3 interface Read more about the system architecture in the architecture & development information section . Interested in using cmail? Try our installation guide and the accompanying upgrade guide . Development Rationale cmail was started out of resignation over the complexity involved in configuring and running many other As such, the configuration file format is relatively simple and only affects the specifics of the module it is written For the most part the configuration files consist of directives specifying on which ports the module should provide its The primary objective of the project is to provide an , and secure mail server for that simply want to send and receive mails on their Other use cases are, of course, supported, but not with as high a The common configuration, such as local addresses, routing decisions and user data are kept in the master This provides flexibility of reconfiguration without restarting the modules, as well as allowing for the use of a variety of interfaces to configure the server, such as the provided Web Panel or an SQLite database cmail was intentionally kept simple in terms of configuration as well as It might not support some features experienced administrators may be accustomed to Most of it can probably be enabled or emulated with sufficient thought, Should that not be enough, you can extend cmail either by modyfing the purposely slim codebase or by interfacing with a (not yet implemented, but planned) internal API for modifying its behaviour with shared libraries (plugins). If cmail still does not meet your expectations after that, you might be better off using another MTA :) Current state & coarse roadmap As the main developers have transitioned from university into jobs, development has slowed However, multiple cmail systems are in full productive use and the architecture has proven to be very The primary criticism so far is missing support for IMAP, which is in slow progress, both due to the aforementioned lack of time as well as the pecularities of the IMAP The following coarse roadmap illustrates the progress we currently aim for Basic implementation (2019) Initial public packaged release (2019) This listing should not be taken at face Development pace is not easy to estimate, and features may be postponed because of lack of interest or more pressing For finer grained lists, check the individual module folders in the repository for files named Common use cases server, mail is sent via external servers The following modules are involved for receiving incoming mail or for access to mailboxes Optionally: and for easier administration Optionally: and for web access to mailboxes server This use case might be better served by nullmailer . Using cmail, you d need for accepting originated mail for delivering the outbound mail Optionally: and for easier administration and This setup involves the following modules for receiving incoming mail and or for access to mailboxes for delivering the outbound mail Optionally: and for easier administration Optionally: and for web access to mailboxes Contributing & Contact Our main development languages are C (daemons), PHP (API backend) and JavaScript HTML (web interface). To get acquainted with the tools we use, our methodology, architecture and codebase, we have aggregated some resources on our architecture & development information page on this web site as well as within the repository . cmail is distributed under the BSD license . Any contributors must agree to have their code placed under that same Got some patches, ideas or questions? Submit pull requests or issues on github , send patches, requests or praise to , discuss ideas and experiences or subscribe to information via one of our other mailing lists or do all of those or simply hang around in our IRC channel - #cmail on freenode . Resources Project homepage: Mailing lists: Currently out of order IRC channel: #cmail on Github organisation: cmail-mta git repository (main): git clone https: github.com cmail-mta cmail git repository (contrib): git clone https: github.com cmail-mta contrib Recording of a Lightning Talk about the project at GPN15 (German) [ slides ] Badges, etc Coverity Scan:

The Open Source Initiative explains it When people can read, redistribute, and modify the source code, software People improve it, people adapt it, people fix The results of development have been efforts to develop software under licenses have produced , code on which much of the Internet is Why for OR? Without open source implementations of existing algorithms, testing new ideas built on existing ones typically requires the and process of (and and ) the original If the original algorithm were publicly available in a community repository, imagine the productivity gains from software reuse! Science evolves when previous results can be easily Our Initiative The project is managed by the Foundation, , a educational We are building an community for operations research software in order to speed development and deployment of models, algorithms, and computational research, as well as provide a forum for peer review of software similar to that provided by archival journals for theoretical Getting Started Mailing List Enter your name and email address in the space below and click Subscribe A confirmation email will be sent to you, asking you to click on a link to complete the CONTRIBUTE There are several ways you can help make better: Download and use software Send us feedback Volunteer your time Contribute code or documentation Our download page describes how to download After downloading, read the INSTALL files for instructions on Check out the documentation available on If you have any trouble, send us feedback! Curv | a language for making art using mathematics Skip to the Curv a language for making art using mathematics View on GitHub Curv is a programming language for creating art using It<U+0092>s a and geometric modelling tool that supports full colour, animation and Features: Curv is a simple, powerful, dynamically typed, pure functional programming Curv is easy to use for It has a standard library of predefined geometric shapes, plus operators for transforming and combining These can be plugged together like Lego to make and Coloured shapes are represented using Function Representation (F-Rep). They can be infinitely detailed, infinitely large, and any shape or colour pattern that can be described using mathematics can be represented Curv exposes the full power of programming to The standard geometry library is written entirely in Many of the demos seen on can be reproduced in Curv, using shorter, simpler Experts can package techniques used on shadertoy as high level operations for use by Rendering is GPU Curv programs are compiled into fragment shaders which are executed on the Curv can export meshes to STL, OBJ and X3D files for The X3D format supports full colour printing (on , at least). These meshes are defect free: watertight, manifold, with no self intersections, degenerate triangles, or flipped curv is maintained by curv3d . This page was generated by GitHub Pages .

Decision Neuroscience of Human Interactions <U+0096> Lab at Heidelberg University Skip to content Decision Neuroscience of Human Interactions Lab at Heidelberg University Home Research People Publications Teaching Contact Decision Neuroscience of Human Interactions Lab at Heidelberg University Main Menu Home Teaching Research People Publications Contact Welcome to the homepage of our research group headed by Christoph Korn at Heidelberg University, Germany ( Section Social Neuroscience , Department of General Adult Psychiatry). We are investigating the D ecision N euroscience of H uman I nteractions with the goal to address the following broad questions: How do humans make social decisions ? How do they learn about each other ? What are the neural underpinnings of such and learning processes? How can we devise computational models ? How do these processes differ in individuals suffering from psychiatric disorders ? How can we develop new diagnostic and therapeutic tools ? Our research projects combine computational modeling of behavioral data, and multivariate analyses of fMRI data , pupillometry , evolutionary game theory, virtual reality, We are strongly committed to open science (e.g., sharing data code and preregistering our studies). The group is funded to a large degree by an Emmy Noether research grant of the German Research Foundation (DFG) and started at the Institute of Systems Neuroscience (University Medical Center , UKE, Hamburg, Germany). The Standard The latest version of the standard, IEEE Std TM , was released , The updated standard contains many changes, including DNP3 Secure Authentication v5, which defines a protocol mechanism that enables a DNP3 outstation master to unambiguously determine that it is communicating with the correct user outstation. appropriate regional and national In these unprecedented times please take care of yourselves and those around Migration Atlas dataset completed Over the last year EURING<U+0092>s member ringing schemes have been hard at work checking and preparing data for the Eurasian African Bird Migration Atlas that is due to be published in Thanks to a huge effort by many people this impressive dataset is now It contains almost million encounter records of marked individuals based on resightings, recaptures by ringers and dead birds reported by the The Atlas will map the migration routes of some species and provide information on migration periods, migratory connectivity, illegal killing of birds and changing migration The dataset will also support a wide range of other Advances in modelling demographic processes The proceedings of the EURING Analytical Meeting and Workshop have been published as a special issue of Methods in Ecology and Evolution and Ecology and Edited by Rob Robinson and Beth Gardner these proceedings bring together a series of papers demonstrating cutting edge statistical methods and their application to a range of issues relevant to data from bird ringing and related ecological Topics covered include and analysis, integrated population modelling, movement analyses and occupancy More information on this highly productive series of conferences is available G+ users join Google+ and Google+ Fail2Ban Users Community Fail2ban scans log files (e.g. var log apache error_log ) and bans IPs that show the malicious signs -- too many password failures, seeking for exploits, Generally Fail2Ban is then used to update firewall rules to reject the IP addresses for a specified amount of time, although any arbitrary other action (e.g. sending an email) could also be Out of the box Fail2Ban comes with filters for various services (apache, courier, ssh, etc). Fail2Ban is able to reduce the rate of incorrect authentications attempts however it cannot eliminate the risk that weak authentication Configure services to use only two factor or public private authentication mechanisms if you really want to protect More about Fail2ban Fail2ban ChangeLog (List of changes) Requirements (Needed requirements for Fail2ban ) Features (List of current and planned features) Issues (Bugtracker) Screenshots (Screenshots) Downloads ( Fail2ban for your distribution) Presentations (Past presentations (slides, videos)) Links (Links related to Fail2ban ) Mailing list (Support and discussions) Google+ and Google+ Fail2Ban Users Community HOWTO Seek Help Documentation README (Official README file) Manual (Official Fail2ban documentation) Configuration (Configuration related to external software) FAQ (Frequently Asked Questions) HOWTOs (HOWTOs contributed by users) Reference Manual (Source code documentation) Proposed documentation for Hostname IP Address Logging Developers Contributors (persons who contributed to the project) Get Involved News See GitHub Releases for most Entries below might be outdated 08 01 is a big bugfix and new functionality Release Notes for . 04 29 is a big bugfix and new functionality Release Notes for . 10 28 is a big bugfix and new functionality Release Notes for . 08 19 is a minor bugfix release primarily to fix Python Release Notes for . initiative The Federated Tumor Segmentation (FeTS) initiative, describes the development of i) the largest international federation of healthcare institutions, and ii) an toolkit with a GUI, aiming at gaining knowledge for tumor boundary detection from ample and diverse patient populations without sharing any patient The FeTS toolkit focuses on: bringing trained segmentation models of numerous deep learning algorithms and their fusion, closer to clinical experts and researchers, thereby enabling easy quantification of new radiographic scans and comparative evaluation of new allowing secure institutional collaborations via federated learning to improve these models without sharing patient data, thereby overcoming legal, privacy, and Successful completion of this project will lead to an tool enabling easy, fast, objective, repeatable and accurate tumor segmentation, without requiring a computational background by the user, and while facilitating further analysis of tumor towards <U+0096> AI WG3 <U+0096> Investments Contact Contact Us All the news from the FinAI Cost Action FinAI The financial sector is the largest user of digital technologies and a major driver in the digital transformation of the Financial technology (FinTech) aims to both compete with and support the established financial industry in the delivery of financial Globally, more than $100 billion of investments have been made into FinTech companies and Artificial Intelligence (AI) since , and continue growing In early , the European Commission unveiled (a) their action plan for a more competitive and innovative financial market and (b) an initiative on AI with the aim to harness the opportunities presented by Europe should become a global hub for FinTech, with the economy being able to benefit from the European Single Objectives The Action will investigate AI and Fintech from three different angles: Transparency in FinTech, Transparent versus Black Box Models in the Financial Industry, and Transparency into Investment Product Performance for The Action will bridge the gap between academia, industry, the public, and governmental organizations by working in an interdisciplinary way across Europe and focusing on The key objectives of the Action are: to improve transparency of AI supported processes in the Fintech space to address the disparity between the proliferation in AI models within the financial industry for risk assessment and , and the limited insight the public has in its consequences by developing policy papers and methods to increase transparency to develop methods to scrutinize the quality of products, especially <U+0093>smart beta<U+0094> ones, across the asset management, banking and insurance Research Goals Develop approaches to evaluate innovative financial services and their providers, especially in the FinTech domain, building on Machine Learning methods, focusing on prediction (early warning) of operational fragility, fraudulent and illegal behavior ranging from appropriation of loaned funds to money laundering Development of conceptual and methodological tools for establishing when models are admissible and, to the extent possible, making them more transparent Receive input from regulators and practitioners<U+0092> communities and validate results with regard to increasing transparency of artificial intelligence Development of methodologies for reducing the false discovery rate in financial research and applied financial investment Disseminate to the public and share with regulators the results on investment product performance Creation of the first European platform comparing the performance of banks<U+0092> investment products, investment products and asset management products available to the general <U+27A1> Join our action Friends of the Bluff is the organization responsible for maintaining and protecting Spokane s High Drive We are a group of hikers, runners, mountain bikers, dog walkers, bird watchers, and nature lovers who work together to maintain the bluff, purely on a volunteer <U+200B> We are a sustainable, organization that - through education, outreach, and direct conservation efforts - ensures that the Bluff will always be a protected, healthy, and natural ecosystem, accessible to all who wish to respectfully enjoy Through volunteer efforts and community partnerships, we organize trail maintenance, fire suppression, invasive plant management, tree planting, park cleanup, and naturalist Everything we do is made possible by the passion and care of the people in our Join us and be a Friend of Bluff! What is the High Drive Blu ff? Hundreds of people drive along High Drive on Spokane s South Hill every day, yet many are completely unaware of the acres of Ponderosa Pine forests and bunchgrass meadows that thrive along a steep hillside This large natural space is known as the High Drive Bluff, and there is a lot more to explore than most people With over miles of trails, the bluff is the perfect spot for anything from a morning stroll to a grueling mountain bike It is also an ideal location for , hiking, , birding, and watching the PRINTABLE TRAIL MAPS DONATE The Friends of the Bluff is a (C)3 nonprofit Your contribution is key to the purchase of tools and other elements that allow us to sustain and conserve the Bluff and its GET INVOLVED Volunteer Events are the core of our efforts to preserve and protect the <U+200B> Volunteer opportunities Become a board member Connect on Facebook PROJECTS Our Current Priorities : <U+200B> Protection from Development Maintaining and Improving Public Access Forest Health Fire Risk Reduction Educating & Engaging the Community Maintaining Sustainable Trails Litter Removal Weed Management BLUFF WALKS Our , educational Bluff Walks are now available Learn all about the bluff from experts like Jack Nisbet, Jerry White from Riverkeeper, and many View Series PLEASE SHOW YOUR APPRECIATION TO OUR COMMUNITY PARTNERS We couldn t do what we do without the help of our local business <U+200B> Please show them some love and be sure to mention that you appreciate their support of Friends of the Bluff! learning community and emphasize While there are no requirements to enroll in these programs, basic computer skills are I have worked with students with no GIS background, limited GIS background, and some with very extensive GIS I believe that the best way to learn GIS is through personal contact between professors and students, who forge a learning community that is not simply a transfer of information from a professor to a student, but is an interactive model of learning in which we help each other extend our Overall, I firmly believe that "what you put into the program is what you will challenge you to move beyond the link between scientific principles and their application in Geographic along with creative and critical thinking will develop your skill base, but such a process HeySugar | Diabetes Management with Jamstack HeySugar Home Docs Github What is HeySugar? HeySugar is an , self hosted, blood sugar management application for type one and type two HeySugar is developed with Jamstack and is made up of two separate applications: An front end to display blood sugar results An application to log blood readings and update the website The front end is developed with Gatsby and the core functionality is passed into a Gatsby website through our Gatsby Theme which means we can release patches and enhancements to users via The blood tracking application has been developed with Sanity . This means you will need to create an account on the Sanity platform in order to use But don t worry! We also created a Sanity plugin to take care of this for Just like the Gatsby Theme, any changes we make to the Sanity Schema will be published through this This means you won t need to make any changes to the Sanity system, unless you want to customise your own instance of Want to Get Started? Head over to our documentation for information on getting started and don t forget, if you experience any problems then raise an issue on our github . Better yet, if you want to contribute then Pull Requests are welcome! Please note: HeySugar is still in the very early stages of development and getting started requires some manual process, but we do help you with a step by step video in the Getting Started section of our This will change in the near future as we continue to work on automating the majority of the setup We use cookies for analytical purposes on these docs in order to understand areas that require We understand that by using this website you acknowledge Project created by Jamie Bradley

<U+FEFF> HPSS Collaboration High Performance Storage System Home About Collaboration HPSS Customers HPSS World Map HPSS Hardware & Interfaces Best of Breed for Tape HPSS for Spectrum Scale HPSS Offerings High Availability HPSS Brochures & Presentations HPSS RAIT HPSS Releases Documentation Users Administrators Services Classes Consulting HUF Contact Us Incremental Scalability Based on storage needs and deployment schedules, HPSS scales incrementally by adding computer, network and storage A single HPSS namespace can scale from petabytes of data to exabytes of data, from millions of files to billions of files, and from a few per second to thousands of per Incremental Scalability Performance & Efficiency Availability & Durability Delivery & Support What is High Performance Storage System? HPSS storage software meets the most challenging long term scalable storage HPSS features reduce the total cost of ownership of data, maximize transfer performance of all file sizes, lower tape cartridge costs, maximize storage utilization, efficiently manage data integrity, and minimize failure recovery There are well known value propositions for the different types of Solid state disks are the best storage option when bandwidth and I O per second are the driving When files are needed immediately and capacity is the driving requirement, hard disk drives may be the best Tape is the most economical storage for infrequently accessed data at scale, and is often called "zero-watt storage". Many storage and cloud providers offer different levels of storage, at different price Learn how HPSS helps with the stewardship of data at + Learn More Highlights Who developed HPSS? HPSS is the result of over two and a half decades of collaboration among five Department of Energy laboratories and IBM, with significant contributions by universities and other laboratories + Learn More Best of breed for tape! HPSS is considered best of breed for tape because of our efficient use of tape hardware and Tape hardware and media efficiency translates to lower total cost of ownership (TCO) of long term data + Learn More Who is using HPSS? HPSS is considered best of breed for tape and offers many compelling features to keep storage costs It is not just data capacity requirements that bring organizations to + Learn Who Is HPSS right for you?? Three of the top five supercomputers on the planet ( Top500 ) use HPSS software to meet their storage Single instances of HPSS support users ingesting and simultaneously recalling petabytes per If you currently store all your data on spinning disk, and you have growing storage needs that currently exceed five petabytes or your current tape solution is delivering abysmal tape performance, an HPSS best of breed tape storage solution from IBM may help lower your storage HPSS can transfer files to tape faster and recall files from tape more efficiently so fewer tape drives are needed to meet storage Simply stated, capacity or requirements are NOT the only reason customers use HPSS! + Learn More Come meet with us! HPSS @ ISC ISC is the event for high performance computing, machine learning, and data analytics, and will be in Frankfurt, Germany from May through June , - Learn More . A machine learning company View My GitHub Profile About Us Iddo Software is currently comprised of Bogdan Budescu, <U+0218>tefan Ghiviriga and Dorian We<U+0092>re, basically, three guys in a basement office writing computer vision and deep learning code for startups that need our skills to build their What we do As I<U+0092>ve stated above, we<U+0092>re (mostly) writing Many computer vision and machine learning apps share common functionality, so we strongly incentivize our clients (through substantial discounts to our own hourly rates) to allow us to reuse the code we write for This way, we don<U+0092>t write the same stuff over and over again (which leads to boredom and depression), and our clients get their code faster and We also have a network of other machine learning and computer vision engineers which we might be able to get on board if necessary, and other developers that can help us out with things like DevOps, web dev, mobile dev, sys admin and What we want We want to We have a strong predilection towards stability and, hence, we value long term commitments from our Reciprocally, we offer long term commitments to our clients in As such, we usually prefer, , hiring new developers for new clients as opposed to switching devs from one customer to the We also like to put our money where our mouth is, so we generally offer a significant discount for contracts with the clients we already have a good history What we<U+0092>ve done As you can see, we don<U+0092>t have a proper portfolio web page yet, since we<U+0092>ve been pretty busy doing what we do best for our clients, namely writing computer vision and deep learning We<U+0092>re actually working on the portfolio, but it<U+0092>s not ready However, in the mean time, you can get a grip of what we<U+0092>ve done until now by taking a look at our LinkedIn Here is Bogdan<U+0092>s, here is <U+0218>tefan<U+0092>s, and here is Dorian<U+0092>s. What we can do As you can find out if you browse our profiles, we<U+0092>re experienced with projects involving: mapping objects in images to their positions in the real world classifying, locating, segmenting and recognizing objects in images, mostly (but not only) using neural nets designing, training and deploying neural nets for the above purposes, and some others, too (e.g., improving video quality) We<U+0092>re also used to having to read a lot (research). This way we<U+0092>ve been able to tackle a large variety of projects, as you can see in our Note: at some point, Bogdan took the time to write everything he could remember having used, in terms of tech, on his personal It<U+0092>s a lengthy (and rather boring) read, but if you want you can access it here . How we do what we do We work closely with our clients throughout every stage of the process of making their ideas happen: understanding the business goals processes identifying stages in the pipeline which might benefit from using a CV ML approach researching the state of the art in the relevant field estimate the relative cost, time to market and expected performance of alternatives we find (or think of) solution design, implementation, testing, deployment and What we use Over time, we<U+0092>ve used several technologies (programming languages, libraries, frameworks ) to build the stuff we<U+0092>ve built, and, in the process, we<U+0092>ve grown more or less accustomed to some of them: Computer Vision: OpenCV (from both Python and C++ ), mahotas , , Deep Learning: TensorFlow ( Python for training & inference, C and Java for inference only), Keras , HyperOpt , , Caffe ( C++ , Python ), Theano , pylearn2 (really old framework) deployment: Docker , OpenAPI , pipenv generic data processing: NumPy statistics: pandas , , statsmodels data visualization: matplotlib (+ mpld3 ), seaborn , plotly GUI: Qt for Python ( PyQt5 , PyQt4 , PySide ) What we have Currently we have a few NVidia GPUs at our disposal for training and deploying neural We also have some code that we wrote for our clients in the past, for which we have kept the right to to further That code may be used for: training and applying neural nets: (bounding box) detectors using TensorFlow<U+0092>s Object Detection API keypoint detectors object segmentation deploying TensorFlow nets using Python, C (so not necessarily C++) and Java deploying nets training and inference services easily and in a scalable fashion using docker generate http endpoints for our deployed inference services quickly and easily using OpenAPI quickly feeding data to the training process of neural nets defined in keras detecting paper documents on flat surfaces green screen removal (keying) accurately estimate the position of objects relative to the camera given a few recognized points which respect some constraints known a priori other stuff I can<U+0092>t remember now, but probably will, if a problem arises that can be Hackathon AWS Build On Singapore Posted on January 4, January , From June to September , HCIRS took part in the Amazon Web Services Build On Singapore After months of grueling preparation, our team comprising Alistair Cheong, Chen Zerui, Wang Yiqin and Wu Jiayang, have emerged as Joint Champions of the Junior Category with their Learning Management System catered to volunteer tuition We would like to thank AWS for organising this competition, as well as the school for giving us the opportunity to embark on this unique learning experience! Cyber Security STACK the Flags Posted on December 6, January , Over the past weekend, HCIRS took part in GovTech Cyber Security Group<U+0092>s inaugural STACK the Flags CTF, and achieved commendable results: Champions Team Mitsusha: Sherman Chann Zhi Shen, Teo Kai Xiang, Choo Zheng Jun, Zhang Yao William Runners Up Team Chomusuke: Beh Chuen Yang, Zhao Zhongqi, Lim See Min, Wu Jiayang Place Team Bear: Zhou Taidi, Luo Hongxun, Lien Cai Ting, Theodore Lee Chong Jen Congratulations to all participants! IMP, the Integrative Modeling Platform home about news download doc source systems tests bugs contact Edit on GitHub IMP, the Integrative Modeling Platform IMP s broad goal is to contribute to a comprehensive structural characterization of biomolecules ranging in size and complexity from small peptides to large macromolecular assemblies, by integrating data from diverse biochemical and biophysical IMP provides an open source C++ and Python toolbox for solving complex modeling problems, and a number of applications for tackling some common problems in a IMP can also be used from the Chimera molecular modeling system, or via one of several web IMP is open source software, mostly available under the terms of the GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL) . (Some IMP modules are available under the GNU GPL ) Get started with IMP by downloading it and checking out the documentation . The IMP software is used as part of the National Center for Dynamic Interactome Research (NCDIR). If you use IMP, please cite Russel, Lasker, Webb, Schneidman, , Sali, "Putting the pieces together: integrative structure determination of macromolecular assemblies", PLoS Biology, . All of these builds are based on Chromium Download News About Iridium Browser is based on the Chromium code All modifications enhance the privacy of the user and make sure that the latest and best secure technologies are Automatic transmission of partial queries, keywords and metrics to central services is prevented and only occurs with the approval of the In addition, all our builds are reproducible and modifications are auditable, setting the project ahead of other secure browser Transparency With Iridium, the whole process is entirely The public Git repository allows a direct view on all changes The complete source code is therefore Privacy Iridium Browser has various enhancements where it forces strict security to provide the maximum level of security without compromising Deployability We try to distribute it in ways where it allows easy installation and yet allows administrators to deploy it An example is an installation mechanism for easy deployments throughout an entire Motivation There are many browsers out Chrome is fast, stable and but does not meet many organizations<U+0092> demands for Since the tight integration with its inventor (Google) makes many things easier, it does not comply to restrictive data Iridium is not another new browser from It takes the Chromium code base and enhances its security and sets certain policies by There are many forks of browsers, yet, in our opinion they failed in many other key areas important for FAQ Learn about Iridium Browser and Available Resources To Step In Please report any issues and address any questions to our bug tracker on GitHub . Before joining the Kottans course, I went to "study" to a small company to a friend of There I was immediately given React docs and told that this is how it After a month of such studies, I realized that I was clearly lacking the And then I came across the announcement of an online course from I took a look at the program - it was just what was And I think that is what all beginners The program is systematized by experienced developers, and includes subjects from the very basics to reasonably advanced things from the development Live communication from the very beginning of the online course with and reviews, an absolutely unique experience that is difficult to obtain even on paid By the way, the lack of a fee in itself is amazing in our time, and at the same time guarantees the transparency of motivation of mentors - they want to help people, and therefore the reviews were as detailed and qualitative as the course left only positive In addition, I got the opportunity to contribute to community life, which is invaluable in I am very satisfied with the course! Almost all of my expectations were confirmed: I found new friends, new colleagues, gained new knowledge, received valuable tips and code When I joined the course, I was already working as a frontend developer knowing HTML, CSS, and some JavaScript basics, but I knew I wanted to have a more solid understanding of modern approaches to JavaScript I am grateful to mentors and active students for their high professionalism and contribution to such a cool community, for their positive attitude, openness, valuable advice and enthusiasm! Personally, I was waiting for the next class not only to get a new batch of knowledge but also to hang out after class))) During the training, we tried to contribute to various initiatives of the Kottans: social network postings, mutual assistance, help to students from the p2p course and so And the pinnacle of teamwork for all of us was the Input Conference, which our cool team succeeded to organize! To our and mentor Oleksiy Rudenko great respect for the fact that he wonderfully led the whole process and was an example for us! In my opinion, communities like this one help to change our country for the better! After all, mutual assistance, communication, and cooperation are the keys to success! I am proud to be a Kottan! And I feel that after the courses I became more professional in my field, and also contributed something useful to this community! It s more than courses, it s a whole family! Every Saturday I wait as a holiday and I have great pleasure in going to But no matter how good is the support and no matter how good are the study materials, it s mainly about your If you do not devote time each day to practice and analyze each source code line, the result will not An easy way into the IT industry is a fairy You need to work on yourself and your But if you still decide to change your life, then you definitely need to go to Only modern technology stack, working programmers as mentors, not one, two, but many, and many of them will always answer your And most importantly, there is no such thing as a stupid question I am very glad that I joined them and became a part of a big Our friends & partners Open the site Open the site Open the site Open the site Open the site Join US + Want to help the community? cut short by cancer or other serious That<U+0092>s why we<U+0092>re developing therapeutics that target the dysregulated transcription that causes cancer and other serious diseases<U+0097>to bring forward novel therapies for patients who need Our Science Our team has the tools, scientific expertise and determination to discover, develop and deliver medicines that reach traditionally Transcription factors have long been attractive to drug developers, who historically have pursued them in isolation with little Our approach is different: We pursue the transcription factors in context, within their transcriptional regulatory networks (TRNs). By analyzing the TRN in its entirety, we can identify the critical nodes that are responsible for a transcription factor<U+0092>s This provides us with multiple avenues to pursue, rather than limiting our focus on a single transcription factor<U+0097>and in turn, allows us to advance programs with the greatest potential to inhibit oncogenic Our Pipeline We have three investigational compounds currently being evaluated for patients with Our two investigational oral SYK inhibitors, entospletinib and lanraplenib, are being developed to treat acute myeloid leukemia (AML). SYK is a critical node in a dysregulated transcription regulatory network within AML defined by persistent high expression of the transcription factors HOXA9 and MEIS1 (HOX MEIS). Together the compounds have the potential to target mutations present in more than of patients with We are also advancing an oral CDK9 inhibitor, , to treat patients with solid tumors addicted to oncogenic transcription factor is the first investigational medicine from our internal discovery platform to enter the Beyond these three investigational compounds, we are progressing additional discovery programs, including one focused on the MYC TRN and another focused on the AR We continue to pursue discovery work across several additional To view our pipelin e, click here . Our Culture Our work is our calling, and we<U+0092>re pursuing it Our team has an established track record with decades of scientific and business We find meaning in making purposeful connections as we seek to bring forward groundbreaking therapies for patients who need We are intensely dedicated and curious<U+0097>and we are taking informed risks to close the gaps between what we know now and what will change the way cancer and other serious diseases are treated in the Our Core Values Empower One Another Embrace The Unknown Turn Impossible Into Inevitable Lead With Heart Careers Join our We<U+0092>re looking for individuals who want to join us as we seek to discover and develop new Our employees in San Mateo, California and Cambridge, Massachusetts are passionate about the scientific problems we<U+0092>re striving to solve and the patients who could one day benefit from the progress we can make See our current list of openings below or submit your resume to . in some muddy spots along the sidewalk and we wanted him to keep away from us, so we nuged him Well, that was play for Major and, unbelievably, in a couple of quick jumps he stood up on his hind legs and put his big muddy paws on the suit lapels of a two We remembered and laughed about that for many Mother<U+0092>s Soon, our mothers began arriving, some arriving with our fathers, and the wonderful gathering began in the We pinned Mother<U+0092>s Day corsages and enjoyed cake, coffee and tea throughout the house, which recalls another We were proudly showing our mothers how clean and orderly our second floor study rooms were, and that brought us to something we weren<U+0092>t sure about: the famous poster of Marilyn Monroe in her birthday suit that we had on the ceiling of our We didn<U+0092>t know if our faces would be turning red, but when our mothers laughed with great spirits we appreciated and loved our mothers even Then it was time for all of us<U+0097>mothers, fathers, family brothers and sisters<U+0097>to gather on the front lawn for the highlight, the iconic Mother<U+0092>s Day photographs that have kept those rare days in our memories all our May , Ethan Rein Feel free to contact us on most major social networks (Twitter, Facebook, Instagram) or via To make the most of your experience, be sure to join our community on Discord for live chat and What is an NFT? A Collectible? A token (NFT) is a unit of data on a digital ledger called a blockchain, where each NFT can represent a unique digital item, and thus they are not NFTs can represent digital files such as art, audio, videos, items in video games and other forms of creative (source Wikipedia ) How much does it cost to create an NFT? Minting an NFT on Stellar costs about 3 XLM mintCost and transfering the NFT on Stellar costs XLM transferCost . Why is it so cheap compared to Ethereum? Litemint is a decentralized marketplace that uses Stellar to process all Stellar is an open network for storing and moving Stellar is specifically designed to power payments of any size with low, flat fees and fast How do I create my wallet? For convenience we recommend installing the Freighter Wallet browser extension, it is like Metamask but for Stellar users! If you prefer a wallet with advanced features such as SDEX access, we recommend using our bespoke Litemint Stellar wallet available on mobile, desktop and web For advanced users we also recommend using . What upload formats are supported? For now we support MP4, JPEG, PNG, GIF, MP3 and This list will be extended to new formats based on demand and use Is there a max upload file size? Max file size is currently This may be extended to cover the needs of artists with MP4 and video Is there a limit on the number of items I can sell? There is no limit besides the max subentries a single Stellar account can have (1000), however you can create any number of wallets to bypass such Is there a royalty system ? Not yet, but we are working on it! We are exploring solutions with Turing Signing Servers for implementing advanced use cases such as royalties with smart contracts on Where is my NFT stored after minting? Litemint is % noncustodial (i.e. you and only you hold and control your items). So your NFTs are always minted directly on your Stellar wallet ( view your collectibles here ) and will remain there till a change of ownership How does the NTF sale and transfer process works? We use the Stellar blockchain for all Stellar provides a decentralized exchange natively ( SDEX ) so when you set an item for sale, you create an offer on the SDEX and the transfer happens automatically, whenever it gets You receive the payment directly as well in your chosen currency, there is no counterparty How do I delete my NFT? It is never possible to fully delete an NFT, the purpose of NFT is to be immutable and permanent so transactions are forever recorded on the It is however possible to burn your NFT by sending it back to the issuer When the supply of an asset is zero, the Litemint marketplace will not show the asset How do I buy or sell using different currency than XLM? Go to your Wallet orders section, click on Explore Market for any How do I get a verified badge? Litemint is for We are not elistists and you do not need to be a celebrity or world VIP to get a verified badge on Litemint! The verified badge is here to help potential buyers assess that they are buying from the real creators or To get a badge, you will need to prove that you are the authentic Just contact us to get What are Litemint decentralized auctions? Litemint Decentralized Marketplace Auctions are time limited auctions tied to a specific market (e.g. XLM, ), no escrow Participants are bound by a smart contract implemented as a transaction that is automatically executed on the Stellar Network with settlement on the Decentralized exchange at the end of the auction The contract is public and guarantees that auction bids cannot be filled before the auction has expired and that the best price is at or above the specified If you own an NFT with a supply of one, issued by a verified account, hosted on .litemint.store, you can start an auction on Regular SDEX bidding and selling are still allowed during an Legal Links Understanding our terms of service and privacy policy is important because, by using Litemint, you<U+0092>re agreeing to these terms: Terms of service Privacy policy Terms of Service Privacy Policy Changelog Minting cost Transfer cost Auction cost Data source: Stellar blockchain Unique items Total sales volume Items sold Artists Monthly Sales Volume (XLM) High blockchain fees are evil but you don t have to pay them . Mini Distribution View on GitHub Mini Distribution A lightweight embedded GNU Linux distribution What is the Mini Distribution? The Mini Distribution is a modern lightweight GNU Linux Distribution for embedded It is built from collections of buildfiles using the Build Gear firmware build The Mini Distribution running on the The Mini Distrubtion also serves as a reference distribution and example on how to create firmware using the Build Gear build It is maintained by the Build Gear maintainers and community It includes a simple set of components and That being said you should be able to easily reuse, modify or extend it for your own In fact, we invite you to adopt the Mini Distribution for your hardware or create your own distribution if you Build Gear makes it easy to do! Features Glibc based toolchain Systemd init system GNU Linux system utilities (no busybox) Small footprint Up to date components Collection of + available buildfiles supporting various features Supported Hardware Currently the lead hardware for the Mini Distribution is the IMX6 Hummingboard from Solidrun . Previously supported hardware included the Raspberry Pi , Beaglebone , and Pandaboard . These are no longer maintained but their buildfiles are still If you would like to maintain the Mini Distribution for any of these boards or other boards please let us Source The buildfiles for the Hummingboard are available here: https: github.com mini-distribution hummingboard All Mini Distribution buildfiles are available here: https: github.com mini-distribution . The main buildfiles are split into 4 collections: core Buildfiles providing basic features (maintained on a regular basis) opt Buildfiles providing optional features (maintained on a regular basis) extra Buildfiles providing extra features (maintained on a basis) Each collection can be split into cross and native Cross buildfiles are those built to run on a host system (eg. arm) different from the system (typically x86) they are built Native buildfiles are those built to run on the same system (typically x86) they are built Generally, it is advised to avoid the use of native buildfiles and instead leverage the features of the available build system components (eg. Ubuntu packages) to reduce maintenance and compilation Downloads Prebuilt images are available http: mini-distribution.io prebuilds . How to install? For install instructions please see the README file in the respective board buildfile For the Hummingboard the README is found here: https: github.com mini-distribution hummingboard . How to build? To build the Mini Distribution you must first install the Build Gear firmware build Then, building the filesystem and bootloader for the Hummingboard is as easy as the following: $ git clone --recursive git: github.com mini-distribution hummingboard.git $ cd hummingboard $ buildgear build fs $ buildgear build This will make Build Gear automatically download the source code of all included filesystem components, resolve build dependencies, and build everything in correct order - the end result is a compressed filesystem tarball in the build output directory: build output fs.tar.gz Likewise the resulting bootloader is available in the build output directory: build output u-boot.img . The build also includes the first stage bootloader: build output SPL For more build details (build system requirements ) see the board README: https: github.com mini-distribution hummingboard . Please notice that it is only supported building the Mini Distribution using Other distributions installed on your build system are not officially However, others will likely work but use on your own risk! Mailing List Subscribe to the following mailing list for development, help, bug reports, announcements, discussions, : Build Gear Development Mailing List Contributing Feel free to contribute - the Mini Distribution is fully open source and open for ideas and patches which improve any of the available build If you want to help out drop by #buildgear and say We are always in need for maintainers to help maintain buildfiles and support for various hardware Mini Distribution Commit History Committer Repository Message Date Hosted by Midphase

Home | Network, Information and Computer Security Skip to main content Skip to search Login links Login Register toggle Main menu Home Members Research Publications Projects Activities Contact Home NICS Lab is an international leading Security research group led by Javier Lopez, Full Professor of the Computer Science Department at University of NICS is composed of persons, including faculty members, researchers, top PhD students, and technical and management staff, all belonging to a major research group GISUM , being distributed on two different locations, the Ada Byron Research Building at the extension of Campus Teatinos and the Computer Science Department at Campus The research activities of the group started back in , when Lopez published his first research work on electronic mail security in Local Area Networks, followed by others on probabilistic primality tests for public keys, and directories security based on Neural Since then, NICS members have published over publications, among them more than journal publications with impact factor (ISI-ranked). Additionally, NICS members have participated in more than security research projects at international and national level, funded by V, VI and VII European Frameworks Programmes as well as by different Ministries in Spain, Japan, Norway and NICS Lab actively participates in international committees and Working Groups in the Security area, as well as in the organization of multiple international conferences and Moreover, NICS is particularly dynamic in the exchange of researchers with other research institutions, having signed official scientific and technical cooperation agreements in US with NIST (Information Technology Laboratory, Computer Security Division), and in Singapore with I2R (Cryptography & Security Department). Over the years, NICS members have been especially active in technology transfer to companies like ATOS Origin, HP Labs, Telefonica, France Telecom, Siemens, Indra, Banesto, Orange, Endesa, Sermepa and Telvent, as well as to public entities like the Spanish Ministry of Defense, the Andalusian Government, and RedIRIS (Spanish advanced communications network for academic and R+D Centres).
