The Occidental Language Toggle navigation Get Started (current) About Learn Tools Read Channels Community FAQs Occidental The International Auxiliary Language Get Started Learn naturally with Salute, Jonathan! Search the dictionary in multiple languages ! Talk to others in the community! What is Occidental? The best way to think of Occidental is as a common Western It s the French or the Spanish you wish you had learned in school, because it keeps the common vocabulary but removes the parts that make them For example, to form the simple past tense you change the r in the verb to a t . And to form the simple future tense, you put a va in front of Yes, you just finished learning the simple past and future Try doing that in two sentences with a natural But because it s a common Western European, it also looks like English liberty and French libert<e9> is libert<e1> , English moon and Spanish luna is lune (think lunar ), English sit and Italian sedere is seder (think sedentary ). It was created in in Tallinn, Estonia, reached its height in Europe just before World War II, went into decline and nearly died in the after which it came back to See Wikipedia for Learn Salute, Jonathan! Natural Acquisition Course Salute, Jonathan! Memrise Flashcards Occidental Course in Lessons (1929, updated ) Grammatica de Interlingue by Fritz Haas Curs de Occidental (Interlingue) by Ric Berger L OCCIDENTAL - Langue d intercompr<e9>hension imm<e9>diate Occidental for English Speakers - Thinking Method Course INTERLINGUE FOR BEGINNERS by Wilfrid Reeve (1966) Manual de Conversation e Corespondentie Tools Community Dictionaries with Search Tatoeba phrase translations Verb Derivation Tool Interlingue spellchecker for Firefox Glosbe dictionary + translation Read Cosmoglotta Cosmoglotta (1927-1950, typed with updated orthography) Modern Cosmoglotta (~2014) Helvetia Helvetia (typed) Li Jurnal (as of August issue will be coming out in a month or so) Pepper & Carrot webcomic Story Translations (with functionality) The Day Boy and the Night Girl by George MacDonald The Little Prince Original Universal Declaration del Jures Homan Classic Culture by Vicente Costalago History by Vicente Costalago Geography by Vicente Costalago Mathematics by Vicente Costalago Original Fiction Li sercha in li castelle Dewahl e altri racontas by Vicente Costalago Antologie hispan by Vicente Costalago Fabules, contes e mites by Vicente Costalago Channels Twitter List for accounts that use Occidental Language Facebook Page Official Language Union Website Community Forums Facebook Group Email List Subreddit Instant Messaging Note : All of these chat rooms are bridged together via Matrix, so you only need to join Telegram Matrix Discord Frequently Asked Questions What about Interlingua, Esperanto, Lingwa de Planeta, and other Auxlangs? What sets Occidental apart from the rest? All auxlangs are made with the best of intentions and deserve Out of the hundreds and even thousands of proposed projects, the ones mentioned above are some of the very few that have ever managed to achieve an active user base, and that makes them Having said that, what makes Occidental unique is the following: It looks like a natural Most people conclude it must be a dialect similar to Catalan or Occitan, spoken in the area between Spain and And that means that: It s remarkably easy to About one or two billion people can work their way through an Occidental text without ever having seen one However, it s still a language created to be as easy as It s a language that you can learn in a few weeks and come out knowing how to read a lot of related languages like Italian and French without having studied them And as the next question shows, you<U+0092>ll come out knowing a lot more about English Some of the auxlangs above have an appearance as natural as Occidental, and others have a grammar as (and even a little bit more) But no language has managed to blend a natural look and regular grammar as well as Occidental That s why it took its creator years to put it I learned about Interlingua first and Occidental (Interlingue) looks really similar to Why do people choose Occidental over Interlingua? By and large it is a bad idea to talk down other planned They all have their own adherents who join them for perfectly good reasons, and their own reasons for staying as Nevertheless, Occidental Interlingu e and Interlingu a have such a close history that mentioning one often results in being questioned about the There was a mass movement of Occidentalists to the and New Interlingua in the (Occidental being and based in Europe). Then there was a similar movement in the opposite direction after the advent of the People who gave Esperanto a try, then gave naturalism a try with Interlingua, eventually discovered that it was Occidental that they were looking for all Part of this comes from the passage of time: Europe is no longer a continent and the original funding for Interlingua has long since dried up (along with the buzz it had in the ). What is left are two languages with fairly active communities that are now only judged on their own So without getting into too much detail, Occidental is for many of us what we hoped Interlingua would be when we were first attracted to it - a planned language that is mostly understandable at first sight, charming and pleasant to look at and listen to, and regular and easy to What does regular and easy to learn mean? The clearest difference is probably seen in De Wahl s Rule which regularizes the creating of words from all verbs except six exceptions, while in student has a lot more to memorize . For more details, we will be adding articles from the old issues of Cosmoglotta in the as they are They can be seen THE MOTE AND THE BEAM (Schematism and naturalism in international languages) Why should I spend time learning Occidental instead of a natural language? Occidental can be thought of as the simplified and tidied up quintessence of the Western European languages, or rather Europe<U+0092>s The common vocabulary is connected but hidden, and Occidental makes it Take the word father for Why is it patre and not some other word? It<U+0092>s because it serves the key role in words related to it that we all patre ( patr <U+00B7>e) father patria ( patr <U+00B7>ia) homeland (fatherland) expatriate (ex<U+00B7> patr <U+00B7>ia<U+00B7>t<U+00B7>e) expatriate (ex means out, from, or out from) patriarch ( patr <U+00B7>i<U+00B7>arch) patriarch patriot ( patr <U+00B7>i<U+00B7>ot) patriot patriotisme ( patr <U+00B7>i<U+00B7>ot<U+00B7>isme) patriotism repatriation (re<U+00B7> patr <U+00B7>i<U+00B7>a<U+00B7>t<U+00B7>ion) repatriation Now in other languages this is hidden: patre is p<e8>re in French (the t is gone), padre in But when we get to the derived terms, we see the t come This is the ingrained common root that Occidental Occidental French Spanish patre p<e8>re padre expatriate expatri<e9> <e9> expatriado a patriarch patriarche patriarca patriot patriote patriota patriotisme patriotisme patriotismo repatriation rapatriement repatriaci<f3>n When you know Occidental, the common roots simply become visible in a way excelled by maybe only Have a look over the following list and see just how clear the vocabulary becomes when expressed in Intervalle (interval), formed from inter (between) and valle (mound, bulwark). Literal meaning: a "between-walls<U+0094>. <cd>nevitabil (inevitable), formed from <ed>n (reverses the meaning), evitar (to evade) <U+2192> evit<U+00B7>abil. Literal meaning: <U+0093>un-evade-able<U+0094>. burgeonant (burgeoning): a burgeon is a bud in Then verbalized as burgeonar <U+2192> burgeona<U+00B7>nt vernal (vernal): Think of the vernal equinox, the day in March when day and night are of equal length and spring officially In Occidental verne means spring radicalisme (radicalism): the word radica means A radical is someone <U+0093>rooted<U+0094> in an seculari (secular): a secul is a century in - ari turns it into an adjective meaning something of this era (something that is a product of its time). nomination (nomination): a n<f3>mine is a This one is easy: a nomination is literally a <U+0093>naming<U+0094>. So when you read Occidental, you have a stronger idea of what the words mean? That s It s almost as if English looked like this, with hints everywhere about the meaning of the words we use everyday: Morning! How was your break fast? Pretty Nothing like breaking your fast with ham and Hey, do we have to work to morrow? Isn t to morrow a holyday? Let s morrow is Odinsday, right? No, that s to day! So to morrow is Oh Any way, the holy day is on Freyday Two days You know what I hate though? Lol, every body hates That s no thing Hey, what do you think of the nameinee for the election this year? They shouldn t have nameinated him, in my Sure, but that s what a nameination is, right? I He said he d increase taxes for people with as much in come as Wait, what? Guys, can some body clearify what that means? It means that making your tax declearation this year is going to But do I have to make a tax declearation even if I lived over seas last year? I was in Uh, may May be not? Ask the nameineee I By the way, did you study hispanish when you were there? I m not very studyous, but I learned more than I thought I Hispanish people love it when you tell them you re What about the uncanny valley? It is a valid concern that Occidental is in the uncanny valley for Romance language speakers in However, see this quote below: The "Uncanny Valley" is much the same as what I ve called the "Rube Effect": a feature of a system that makes me feel illiterate for using [...] My point was that if there is a slight resemblance between the new system and ones already known, you can accept it as coincidence and use it as a mnemonic, but if the resemblance is great, then any deviation will be perceived as an Thus the "Romance" aspect of Esperanto is fairly low, so it doesn t bother me when it does something But when Interlingua does something , such as not having multiple negation (which Occidental does allow), it not only seems wrong, but almost deceptive: I feel set up, taken in by its Romance Because Occidental doesn t look entirely Romance (the pronoun "it," past tense in , "lass," "mey," ) I may find it annoying, perhaps, but I don t feel I once wrote that when you visit Interlingua, it answers the door in a Romance mask, ushers you inside, exchanges pleasantries, and goes to get you some Then it pours the tea on your head and reverts to the "Is something wrong?" When you visit Occidental, it resembles some Romance languages you ve known, but it looks more like a creole of Romance and It almost immediately slaps you in the face, says, "I m not Romance," and then invites you in and is a gracious In other words, it establishes independence early on, and you either accept it or Interlingua maintains a Romance guise most of the time, only to do something really alien when you aren t expecting This is why I kept seeing native speakers of Romance languages trying to fix Interlingua: when you try something that seems odd, even though the grammar may specifically permit it, you re You cannot really say "Ille vide me," even though it s technically allowed (it is completely acceptable as "Il vide me" in Occidental). Steve Rice in Auxlang Listserv Esperanto and other auxlangs only use a few suffixes to form words while Occidental has quite a Why not use fewer? The suffixes in Occidental are in fact already present in Esperanto and similar languages (substanco, direktoro, sentimento, spekulativa, ). The difference is that in Occidental these are regularly formed using its own internal rules (sub + star + = substantie, directer + = director, sentir + = sentiment, specular + de Wahl s rule + iv = speculativ, ) and do not need to be imported as foreign [More details] What if we need to create new words today? Occidental was created to follow a natural evolution similar to the natural languages, where usage or lack of it decides the fate of a And Occidental s large body of literature and wealth of suffixes taken from the natural languages makes the creation of new words Here for example is an article published in on atomic theory in Occidental when the field was completely new, showing how easily it dealt with the new nomenclature with words such as atomic (atom<U+00B7>ic), ionisation (ion<U+00B7>isar - ion<U+00B7>isa<U+00B7>t<U+00B7>ion), resonantie (re<U+00B7>son<U+00B7>ar - re<U+00B7>sona<U+00B7>nt<U+00B7>ie), and so Because of this, the best way to create new words is to simply learn the language On top of this, Occidental does not require any specific endings for words so international words can generally be imported without Occidental looks very Does a word in Occidental have to match a Romance word to be correct? Not at Occidental tends to form words that either match an existing international word, are very close to one, or one that other languages could have created themselves but simply have We do not hesitate to form words like <U+0093>ludette, plorada, substantival, pruntation, credaci, perdibil, leonello, musicastro, plumallia, tassade, sucrage, glotton, stridore, hesitatori, successosi, flexura<U+0094> without asking ourselves whether these words are international or always represent forms that living languages would have been able to produce using their own Alphonse Matejka in Autonomie e Regularita in li Lingue International (1948) How can I get involved with the Occidental language and contribute? The fun thing about Occidental as a language is that you can start to contribute to it and give it new life pretty quickly after getting the basics On top of that, because it is also an auxlang with a long history, it has a lot of existing content and established infrastructure that new languages are still working That means it has: A Wikipedia that you can contribute It has its own Wiktionary , but you can also add the Occidental equivalents to words on Wiktionaries in other languages as See the translations in airport , for In Glosbe you can add words and translation Translation memories are very important as they show how a word works in Here is one example . To add translation memories you can go through the back issues of Cosmoglotta here and look for sentences to translate into English or your own You can add sentences to Tatoeba as As of August , Occidental (Interlingue) has over phrases and is in You can translate some of the content from the English Wikipedia page on Interlingue into your own This page was recently added to and has become 5 times larger and more detailed than it was a year ago, so there is a lot of new information to translate into other And of course, just by learning the language and interacting with the community , you are contributing! <U+00A9> Contribute on GitHub

OOPSpam API uses many different measurements to determine what seems to be spam and what does This includes multiple outputs from Machine Learning algorithms, blocklisted IPs lists, spam words, and many more custom The user (you!) directs their content to run through OOPSpam API and will get a Spam Score . This score gives you control for how conservative or liberal you would like to mark as Why do you provide a Spam Score instead of giving a simple <U+0091>yes<U+0092> or <U+0091>no<U+0092>? Because in the real world, things are not black and white (or in this case, green and red)! What might be the best solution for one client could look very different than the We<U+0092>ll give an Say you are a travel website offering high end tour You unfortunately get a lot of spam in your contact form, but it<U+0092>s also the biggest conversion tool you In this case, since missing a <U+0091>real<U+0092> message would mean missing out on large amounts of money, you would want to be more liberal on what content you On the other hand, if you have a travel blog where comments are nice to get but more inconsequential, you might want to be more conservative on what comments you accept so you don<U+0092>t need to spend lots of time combing through potential real We decided to provide this spam score as a way to give developers and website managers more control and ability to create something more custom to <U+0091>WOW<U+0092> their clients . What does the Spam Score look like? The API will return Spam Score which will be a number between 0 to Besides Spam Score, It will also contain other details . It is up to you to decide your threshold based on Spam Score . Usually, a score 3 or above can be considered as Is a request to OOPSpam API stored? AADL relies on abstraction for modeling embedded systems, coupled with an extensive set of properties to precise all configuration It is complemented with annex languages that help refining its The first volume of annexes defines patterns for modeling IMA systems, behavior or data See AS5506 2 standard for more AADL relies on both a graphical and textual syntax to model a system, the example below is a subset of a basic model, with one periodic package foo_pkg public -- sample AADL model thread foo features a : in event data port properties Dispatch_Protocol = Periodic Compute_Execution_Time = 5 ms .. ms Source_Text = "foobar" end foo end foo_pkg Several tutorials for AADL are provided in the blog section of this They illustrate the various steps from basic modeling phases down to analysis and code AADL tutorials <U+00BB> Back to top Tool support for AADL AADL is backed by several tools, covering many engineering steps, from modeling down to various steps of analysis: scheduling, safety and reliability, model checking and code Such diversity supports the engineering of complex systems in a Tools are presented as part of tutorials on AADL tools <U+00BB> Back to top Resources around AADL AADL is a large modeling We provide several examples to help learning its concepts, and show how to use the notation and associated AADLib aims at gathering examples for teaching AADLib <U+00BB> Tutorial <U+00BB> This work is licensed under a Creative Commons Unported License <U+0096> About

Effective Computation in Physics - Field Guide to Research with Python - By Anthony Scopatz & Kathryn Huff - O Reilly Media Physics <U+21D4> Computing Menu Table of Contents Target Audience Installation <U+21D2> Step 1 Step 2 Shop at O Reilly About Us Contact Us Install Errata Contact Us Buy Now! Effective Computation in Physics Now available from O Reilly Media in print and ebook formats! <U+21D4> Also checkout the Finally! Effective Computation in Physics is a manual for starting up or honing your programming and software skills even though your background is in the physical sciences or This book is your field guide to computing and research in the context of the work that you are already We cover all of the big topics that you ll need, from how to program in Python , how to use important Python third party libraries such as NumPy and Pandas , how to interact with the command line, how to write quality publications using LaTeX , and we even dive into the social aspects of science and software development by teaching you Git and GitHub . This book is aimed at people from all We take this to mean physics, astronomy, astrophysics, geology, geophysics, climate science, applied math, biophysics, nuclear engineering, mechanical engineering, material science, electrical engineering, and more! All too often in the physical sciences, people are asked and expected to "just pick up" the computational aspects of their work as they This may have been a reasonable expectation in decades But now there is so much going on in computer science and software development that it is impossible to keep up, let alone get As both authors have run this gauntlet and survived, we understand the perspective and challenges of physical scientists and engineers who are starting out in computing - no matter what point they are at in their Effective Computation in Physics will give you the computational foundation that you need to succeed in your Table of Contents Foreword by Greg Wilson of Software Carpentry Chapter 1 - Introduction to the Command Line Chapter 2 - Programming Blast Off with Python Chapter 3 - Essential Containers Chapter 4 - Flow Control & Logic Chapter 5 - Operating with Functions Chapter 6 - Classes and Objects Chapter 7 - Regular Expressions Chapter 8 - NumPy: Thinking in Arrays Chapter 9 - Storing Data: Files & HDF5 Chapter - Important Data Structures in Physics Chapter - Analysis and Visualization Chapter - Performing in Parallel Chapter - Deploying Software Chapter - Building Software Pipelines Chapter - Local Version Control Chapter - Remote Version Control Chapter - Debugging Chapter - Testing Chapter - Documentation Chapter - Publication Chapter - Collaboration Chapter - Licenses, Ownership, and Copyright Chapter - Further Musings on Computational Physics Physicists & Engineers This book is full of topics, examples, and exercises that are relevant to the physical Software Developers We don t skimp on teaching the important aspects of software development that impact the physical Educators This book was written with the intention of being used as supplemental course Feel free to use it in your Installation Please follow the instructions below to set up your To follow along with the code examples and work on the exercies in Effective Computation in Physics , you ll first need to install some Everything that you need is free and open source . We will be using the conda package manager for all of our installation Step 1: Download & Install Miniconda If you have not done so already, please download and install Miniconda is Python distribution that comes with conda, which we will then use to install everything else we To download miniconda, please visit http: conda.pydata.org miniconda.html and find the version that is right for your Linux, Mac OSX, and Windows builds are available for and You do not need administrator privileges on your computer to install We recommend that you install the Python 3 version of All of the examples in this book should work with Python 2 as If you are on Windows, you can install miniconda simply by double clicking on the executable and following the instructions on the installation Special Windows Instructions - msysGit and Git Bash: If you are on Windows, please download and install msysGit, which you can find at http: msysgit.github.io . This will provide you with both the version control system called git as well as the bash Both of these we will discuss at length and are not automatically available on Windows or through The default install settings should be good enough for purposes If you are on Linux or Mac OSX, first open your Terminal If you do not know where your terminal lives, uses your operating system s search functionality to find Once you have an open terminal, type in the following after the dollar sign ($). Note that you may have to change the version number in the filename (the part) to match the file that you In the above we have downloaded miniconda into our default download directory, ~ Downloads . The name of the file that we downloaded also depends on the version of miniconda that we grabbed as well as whether it was or You may have to adjust the file name On all Linux, Mac OSX, and Windows, when the installer asks you if you would like to automatically change or update the bashrc file or the system PATH , say That will make it so that miniconda is automatically in your environment and will ease further Otherwise, all of the other default installation options should be good Step 2: Install the Packages Now that you have conda installed, we can install the packages that we need for this On Windows open up the command prompt, . On Linux and Mac OSX, open up a You may need to open up a new terminal window for the installation of minconda to take Now, no matter what your operating system is, type the following command: This may take a few minutes to After this, you are ready to go! Kathryn Huff Kathryn Huff is a Fellow with the Berkeley Institute for Data Science and a postdoctoral scholar with the Nuclear Science and Security Consortium at the University of California In , she received her in Nuclear Engineering from the University of Wisconsin She also holds a bachelor s degree in Physics from the University of She has participated in varied research including experimental cosmological astrophysics, experimental granular material phase dynamics, computational nuclear fuel cycle analysis, and computational reactor accident At Wisconsin, she was a founder of The Hacker Within scientific computing group and has been an instructor for Software Carpentry since Among other professional service, she is currently an division officer in the American Nuclear Society and has served two consecutive years as the Technical Program of the Scientific Computing with Python (SciPy) Kathryn s Website The Book This book was heavily inspired by the work of Software Carpentry and The Hacker Within . We are thrilled to see Effective Computation in Physics come to press and spread the joys of computation further into the physical In case you were wondering, the cuddly creature on the cover is a bobtail squid . Buy It Now! Anthony Scopatz Anthony Scopatz is currently an Associate Professor at the University of South Carolina in the Nuclear Engineering program in the Mechanical Engineering He is a computational physicist and long time Python Anthony holds his BS in Physics from UC, Santa Barbara and a in Mechanical Nuclear Engineering from UT A former Enthought employee, he spent his studies at the FLASH Center at the University of Chicago in the Astrophysics Then he became a Staff Scientist at the University of in Engineering Anthony<U+0092>s research interests revolve around essential physics modeling of the nuclear fuel cycle, and information theory & Anthony is proudly a fellow of the Python Software Foundation and has published and spoken at numerous conferences on a variety of science & software development Anthony s Website Questions? Example Problem Definition Suppose we want to generate simple linear equations to be included in a student s mathematics We ll generate equations of the form a x + b = c where a and x are small positive numbers and b and c are positive and possibly C Source (what you write) Let s use the C interface to implement our equation The abstraction it provides is a random number generator with perfect foresight <U+0097> it will never return values that lead to trouble later We ll ask it to uniformly sample values for a , x , b , and c filtered by the condition that the equation actually Simply sampling random integer coefficients without constraint doesn t work because the equation is very likely to have a fractional solution (e.g., 2 x + 1 == 2 implies x == ), a situation that might not be appropriate for students at their current level of int main() if(oracle_acquire()) Fork alternative executions int a = oracle_uniform_int(1, ) Draw integer values from the int x = of data to be returned through calls like oracle_uniform_int that witness a safe execution path that passes through oracle_release without failing any oracle_ensure Once such witness values have been + [b=14] == [c=68] $ spike $INFERENCE_CONFIG pk . example [a=4] [x=3] + [b=77] == [c=89] Inference Let s consider two backend systems that are up to the task of sampling feasible The first, based on Particle Filtering , is easier to understand because it s Rejection Sampling approach mimics how we, as humans, might try to draw samples by simply trying many Upon reaching oracle_acquire , we ll ask the operating system to fork a copy of the currently running process and set a different random When the forked process needs to execute oracle_uniform_int , it simply uses existing random number If the oracle_ensure check fails, the forked process exits without yielding a If oracle_release is successfully encountered, the forked process relays the sequence of random values it used to the master process and then exits as Eventually, the master process will get the data it needs to safely continue execution where the programmer might be watching it in a debugger or waiting to capture its output in a file, and samples will have been drawn with the correct A refined variant of this approach ( Particle Cascade ) powers tools like Probabilistic C . A backend system based on this approach will be very fast to start up and will quickly return solutions if the search problem is easy : when a significant fraction of the potential executions are feasibile ( oracle_ensure checks pass). For hard problems, where the chance of hitting a feasible execution via forward sampling is astronomically low, an approach that can exploit the deep structure of the search problem is In the second approach, we ll use formal verification techniques to seek out those extremely rare Software model checkers, such as CBMC , work by transforming the program into a constraint satisfaction solvers for these problems then either find a satisfying solution (the ingredients of a feasible execution trace) or formally prove that no solutions In exchange for longer times, these approaches provide the best available performance on hard search Care is needed to ensure that the solutions resulting from this process arise with the correct distribution, however recent research on approximate probabilistic inference provides a solid theoretical foundation For resource constrained environments that cannot host the solving process, this computation can be securely delegated to an external service in a new kind of cloud computing Because our users will be expressing both easy and hard search problems <U+0097> what matters is that the problems are easy for human programmers to express in languages <U+0097> Quasilinear Research provides several backend inference systems that make different design Newly developed backends will be compatible with existing compiled software that targets the fixed Probabilistic Defining search problems at the level of machine language allows inference providers to exploit a specification of the search problem without requiring users to reveal their private source Users may program in the language of their choice, even if that language is internal to their organization (presuming it can be compiled for or interpreted by our probabilistic machine abstraction). Probabilistic Processors Quasilinear Research is developing a probabilistic processor model , defined in the Chisel hardware description language, to capture the execution of software in terms of the logic primitives understood by existing search and inference Depending on the type of work performed in the user s probabilistic program, different probabilistic processor models will be appropriate (e.g., including or excluding hardware support for complex math operators, and varying the effective number of parallel hardware threads or harts ). About RationalWiki Our purpose here at RationalWiki includes: Analyzing and refuting pseudoscience and the movement Documenting the full range of crank ideas Explorations of authoritarianism and fundamentalism Analysis and criticism of how these subjects are handled in the media . We welcome contributors, and encourage those who disagree with us to register and engage in constructive dialogue . We have 7,455 articles for your Random featured article [ What is this? ] Genetically modified food Laws regarding Genetically modified food (more correctly, genetically engineered food or transgenic food , and often abbreviated as GM [genetically modified], GMO [genetically modified organisms], and GMF [genetically modified food]) is any food derived from organisms which had their genomes modified using the technique of DNA recombination . Via DNA recombination, genetic material is isolated from one organism and introduced into DNA recombination has the advantages that the source and target organisms need not be sexually compatible and that transfer of genes can be highly specific (introducing only a single desired trait), unlike conventional breeding, which requires sexual compatibility and results in offspring with a mixture of traits from both GMF has recently become the subject of intense Opponents of GMF (predominantly, though not at all exclusively , liberal ) claim that GMF production has adverse environmental impacts , that GMF consumption has adverse health effects, that it s inherently unnatural , and that GMF companies (notably Monsanto ) are screwing farmers and or plotting to control the world food supply . Proponents of GMF claim that GM technology has been the subject of a manufactroversy and accuse opponents of spreading misinformation through the media . rdesktop: A Remote Desktop Protocol Client Toggle navigation rdesktop Releases Issues Repository rdesktop is in need of a new Please see here for more rdesktop is an open source UNIX client for connecting to Windows Remote Desktop Services, capable of natively speaking Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) in order to present the user s Windows rdesktop is known to work with Windows server versions ranging from NT 4 terminal server to Windows Server Overview rdesktop currently runs on most UNIX based platforms with the X Window System, and other ports should be fairly rdesktop is released under the GNU General Public License (GPL), version Please send feedback, bug reports and patches to the appropriate mailing Patches could also be submitted as a pull request on GitHub . rdesktop project is hosted on See the GitHub rdesktop organization for more Download The latest stable version of rdesktop is currently Previous versions of rdesktop releases and corresponding change logs are available at the release page of rdesktop project on You can also download a snapshot of current development version which may be intermittently unstable while new features are Documentation The rdesktop file release contains documentation on the The RDP protocol itself is essentially an extension of the (aka ) application sharing Microsoft has recently made RDP specifications openly available via the MSDN library . Community This project has the following three mailing lists hosted by google groups : Announcements Moderated announcement list for new releases and other important Subscribe Users Support and general discussion list for users of Please use this list for bug Subscribe Development Discussion list for rdesktop This list is used for patch submissions and other development Subscribe Bounties rdesktop project is registered with Bountysource which make it possible for users to create bounties for an issue that they want to get fixed, or just back an existing Donations to the rdesktop project are also handled through The rdesktop team will use the donations to back new or existing If you are a programmer that need some extra Fix the issue that is backed with a bounty and create a pull When the pull request is accepted and merged you should claim the bounty on Bountysource and the backers will vote for For more information about how this all work, read the FAQ at SeamlessRDP A SeamlessRDP server extension is available to support integration of individual applications with the client The minimum requirements for running SeamlessRDP components is Windows Server or SeamlessRDP is released under the GNU General Public License (GPL), version Please send feedback, bug reports and patches to the appropriate mailing SeamlessRDP is a sub project of rdesktop which now has its own repository and issue tracker . Precompiled binaries are unfortunately not available right We hope to be able to provide them in the Professional Services Professional services, such as custom development, is offered by the following companies: Cranberry (UK) Revolution Linux (Canada) (USA) (Germany) If you want to be included in this list, please contact us on the developers mailing Please note that your web site must mention "rdesktop" and link to .

Relational Data Systems - RDS Contact Us Careers Relational Data Systems About us Relational Data Systems (RDS) has been enabling our customers to achieve their digital transformation goals in the lodgement, registry and geospatial business domains since RDS combines our business domain expertise with our passion for technology to design and implement solutions to achieve your strategic goals with highly scalable, secure and reliable information RDS has been part of the Land Services SA group of companies since January , providing access to increased operational and technology experience in the Land and Registry business RDS<U+0092> commitment to quality and security has been demonstrated through our implementation of an ISO27001 and ISO9001 certified Quality and Information Security Management What We Do RDS works with our customers to help define their strategic visions for digital Through this process RDS works with our customers to identify the highest value opportunities and a path to implementing solutions to meet the organisation<U+0092>s Online Lodgement RDS has extensive experience implementing lodgement portals for government and regulatory These portal<U+0092>s provide guided workflows for your customers to submit applications and statutory instruments, providing: A detailed validation and business rules <U+0096> reducing the likelihood of rework Full integration with processing workflows, ensuring a seamless experience Realtime updates and communication with clients, providing process transparency Lodgement portals include: NTG Survey Approvals Online NTG Development Applications Online ACT Government Buyer and Seller Verification NT EPA Online lodgement portal Electronic Registries RDS has developed a wide range of registry systems for our customers, including: Land Title Registries - see Land Information Systems below The NTG Water Licence and Permits System The NT EPA Online lodgement portal Land Information Systems The RDS team have implemented and continue to enhance three Australia integrated land information systems: SAILIS <U+0096> The South Australian Integrated Land Information System ACTLIS <U+0096> The Australian Capital Territory Land Information System ILIS <U+0096> The Northern Territory Integrated Land Information System Recent achievements on these systems include: Transition of % of all Land Transfer dealings lodged in South Australia from paper to electronic, allowing instant recording of the Title Register while reducing error rates and Automatic validation and registration of % of electronically lodged dealings within South Australia, significantly reducing examination and registration Spatial Data Management RDS has partnered with our customers to implement a wide range of spatial data management These solutions include: South Australian Digital Plan Lodgement - Spatial and mathematical processing of electronically lodged plans, allowing online rendering, upfront validation and spatial processing of CAD drawing NR Maps - NR Maps is a web mapping tool to discover, research and map natural and cultural research data for the Northern RDS worked with NTG to implement NR Maps, including the integration of spatial layers from a variety of RDS continues to work NTG to enhance NRDB <U+0096> NRDB is the NTG primary Natural Resource information The RDS team worked with the NTG to expand the range of dataset managed within this database and the publish relevant datasets to NR Spatial Territory Resource Information Kit for Exploration (STRIKE) <U+0096> STRIKE provides spatial representations of scientific and tenure information related to minerals and The RDS team worked with the NTG to implement STRIKE, including integrating a wide range of natural resource and tenure datasets into a single dissemination Certifications ISO9001 RDS has proudly maintained an ISO9001 certified Quality Management System since , ensuring a continued focus on process improvement and customer Annual independent audits of this system are performed by SAI ISO27001 RDS is proud to announce the ISO27001 certification of our Information Security Management System in March Annual independent audits of this system are performed by BSI Adelaide office Level 9, Grenfell Street Adelaide GPO Box Adelaide SA (08) Darwin office Level 2, Smith Street Darwin PO Box Darwin NT (08) [email protected] Terms of use Privacy Accessibility Sitemap Relational Data Systems (ACN ) <U+00A9> Copyright Scroll back to top

Real Vegan Cheese Home Projects FAQ Team News Get Involved Home Projects FAQ Team News Get Involved Real Cheese: , What is Real Vegan Cheese? Real Vegan Cheese (RVC) is a grassroots, research project working to produce real cheese using cellular We add the genes for cheese proteins to yeast and other microflora, and turn them into little protein factories, then make real cheese by adding fats and Real Vegan Cheese is not a cheese substitute -- the cheesemaking process is just like using cow or goat milk! We are dedicated to Open Science and making sure the results of our research are available to the global community to enable a sustainable dairy PROJECTS Want to know what we are working on? Check out our different projects, from casein protein expression to growing the LEARN MORE About Get to know more about Real Vegan Cheese by reading our Frequently Asked FAQ get involved There are many ways to get involved and contribute to the Real Vegan Cheese Find Out How Open Science We are dedicated to Open Science and making sure the results of our research are available to the global community to enable a sustainable dairy International Outreach We<U+0092>ve paved the way for international research efforts, hosting and presenting at events around the community RVC is made possible by the combined efforts of our team of biohackers and citizen scientists working out of two open community labs in the San Francisco Bay Area: Counter Culture Labs in Oakland, CA and BioCurious in Sunnyvale, Back to Top Donate Media Press Kit Contact

Code Replicability in Computer Graphics Code Replicability in Computer Graphics The Project The Data The Team Contribute The Project Being able to duplicate published research results is an important process of conducting research whether to build upon these findings or to compare with This process is called <U+0093>replicability<U+0094> when using the original authors artifacts (e.g., code), or <U+0093>reproducibility<U+0094> otherwise (e.g., algorithms). Reproducibility and replicability of research results have gained a lot of interest recently with assessment studies being led in various fields, and they are often seen as a trigger for better result diffusion and In this project, we assess replicability in Computer Graphics, by evaluating whether the code is available and whether it works As a proxy for this field we compiled, ran and analyzed codes out of papers from SIGGRAPH conferences (exhaustive for , and ). In the analysis described in Nicolas Bonneel, David Coeurjolly, Julie Digne, Nicolas Mellado, Code Replicability in Computer Graphics , ACM on Graphics (Proceedings of SIGGRAPH ), :4, we show a clear increase in the number of papers with available and operational research codes with a dependency on the subfields, and exhibit a correlation between code replicability and citation This website provides an interactive tool to explore our results and evaluation It also provides tools to comment on the various codes either as an author or as a All materials (data, ) that have been used to generate these results are available on the GitHub project . The website contains the data for all papers in: SIGGRAPH SIGGRAPH SIGGRAPH and partial data for: SIGGRAPH ASIA SIGGRAPH SIGGRAPH SIGGRAPH As a long term goal, we would like to collect data for more SIGGRAPH venues, for SIGGRAPH ASIA editions, for ToG papers, and for any other computer graphics If you want to help, see contributions , and check out the contributors . Our project aims at providing the community with tools to improve Computer Graphics research While the Graphics Replicability Stamp Initiative (GRSI) encourages authors to make their research replicable, in our project we check whether existing research is You can contribute new code analysis for computer graphics We re looking forward to your contributions . You can also contact us . Data Digest Key numbers Number of papers reviewed: Number of reviews: Number of papers with code: Number of replicable papers: Number of review year of publication Replicability results for reviewed papers PDF accessibility for reviewed papers Explore Explore the data and our replicability scores Analyze Read our Siggraph paper on analyzed Siggraph Contribute Add comments or new analyses for Computer Graphics reviews so far The Team Nicolas Bonneel (CNRS, LIRIS, Lyon, France) David Coeurjolly (CNRS, LIRIS, Lyon, France) Julie Digne (CNRS, LIRIS, Lyon, France) Nicolas Mellado (CNRS, IRIT, Toulouse, France) Acknowledgments This work was funded in part by (ROOT), (CAL- iTrOp), (CoMeDiC) and (e- ROMA). We also thank Altmetric for providing us access to their Altmetric Attention Contribute There are several ways in which you can contribute and help us improve Computer Graphics research replicability Add a comment (alternative compilation tricks, details on the ) via the discussion on each paper Add a new variant (replicability test), edit an existing JSON file (see below). Add a new entry to the system (new paper), submit a new JSON For the last two cases, you can either submit a proper JSON file as a pull request to this project , or send the JSON file to . Note about : we accept the reviews provided by the authors of a These reviews will be clearly identified and may be double checked to validate the If you re an author, please clearly mention it when submitting your In our system, the website is fully generated from data available on JSON You can browse the database on the github project page . Each paper is a single JSON file, named by the paper DOI, with multiple "variant" Each variant is a build test on a specific system, environment or For example, an article with DOI 2601097.2601102 has a file which looks like [ .... ... data for variant A ... ... , .... ... data for variant B ... ... , .... ] We highly recommend having a look to our template JSON with all the explanations about the fields we are If you have any question, feature requests or found any bug, do not hesitate to report an Issue . Contact us Drop us an email for more information or to let us know what you GitHub <U+00A9> All rights Design: HTML5 UP

sahuKART | Thoughts on eCommerce sahuKART | Thoughts on eCommerce Saturday, December 1, Shows Immaturity of US eCommerce Sites to Global Competition Retailers and online sites in the US take the holiday shopping season There is strong demand for promotions and marketing usually is centered around bringing in as many shoppers to stores and eCommerce sites as In some cases, marketers have invented days such as Amazon s Prime However, the total traffic volume in the US pales when compared with larger Asian Global eCommerce giant Alibaba invented a similar promotional day in China for November as Singles In , Alibaba reported its Singles Day sales surpassed US$30 To put that number in context, Amazon s Prime Day in was expected to account for US $4 Billion in sales while the biggest eCommerce shopping day in the US so far has been Cyber Monday with sales of US$6.6 Even the largest US site wouldn t be able to handle the traffic and sales volumes of In , major US eCommerce sites, including Amazon, and , experienced outages of several For Amazon, the major outage was during the much hyped, much publicized, and shopping event of Prime For , the major outage was on Thanksgiving Day, just as it was kicking off many of its Black Friday promotions That these outages came during their busiest times of promotional period indicates that there is still a challenge they need to All of the marketing and are wasted time and money if customers aren t able to take advantage of those promotions and These frequent and recurring outages indicate a lack of insight into expected traffic volumes, burst capacity planning and testing to those expected Most eCommerce sites utilize either their production environment during overnight hours or a separate performance testing Typically, such environments are % or % of production Testing on such environments will require similar downward adjustments to traffic Rather than test the resiliency of the production environment and multiples of expected traffic and transaction rates, these sites end up testing a fraction of the volume and certifying the production environment using With cloud computing rapidly becoming a viable alternative to hosting, there is value in moving the performance testing environment to the This can also function as a disaster recovery environment if necessary in a Planning and proper execution will be necessary to deliver such an With the elastic nature of cloud computing, and billing based on usage, such environments can cost a small fraction of the environment of similar size and Code optimization will be required in order take advantage of cloud While some of the optimization may arise from code changes to adapt to cloud, most optimizations are within the realm of the operations team that typically manage the More on the cloud computing advantages in future Posted by sahuKART | Thoughts on eCommerce at 3:48 PM comments: Home Subscribe to: Posts (Atom) About Me Lecturers without borders Scientists Lectures Schools & Universities Projects About us FAQ Support Us Give a lecture | Host a lecture Enabling [travelling] scientists to inspire [high] school students Register as a scientist Register as a school ES RU FR PT IT GR "Big thank you note for the wonderful, insightful I received great feedback from the students, they all wrote they learned a lot and they thought the lecture was great and the lecturer was wonderful" Gabriela Ivan First Tech Challenge Romania "I very much enjoyed the opportunity to reach out to the students so enthusiastic about learning, and the atmosphere created on lectures is always the most encouraging about sharing the knowledge!" Georgy Makhatadze University of Copenhagen "It was very good opportunity for my students and me to learn new things and to reach new " Jagoda Ukaj School Teacher, Serbia Lecturers Without Borders Who we are We are a NGO that aims to organize scientific talks in schools around the world, whenever scientists travel to attend conferences or for other The lectures can be in any language that the scientist is fluent in, the work of the scientists is voluntary and all activities are free of charge and can be either in person or Learn more I am a scientist How can I give a lecture? Your lectures can be about your topic of expertise, about a general topic related to your research or about "life as a scientist". The first step to give one is to register on our database so that we can contact you and have the information we need to coordinate your Please note that registering does not involve committing to any immediate action! The next steps depend on whether you re travelling soon or not: I ll be travelling soon I m not travelling yet I ll be travelling soon I m not travelling yet Share your travel plans Tell us where you re going and when, either using this form or by email . Please include all relevant information (e.g. time constraints) We find a school We will contact schools in your destination and find one willing to host your It would be useful for this step to have your online profile available here We schedule the lecture We will find a time during your trip when the school can host your lecture and arrange the details so that it doesn t disrupt your plans too much! Create an online profile Create a scientist profile on our dedicated page so that schools can see it and invite you to their classroom Propose a webinar If you want, you can add webinars to our catalogue using this form , so that schools can request to host them A school invites you Schools can request your webinar or simply invite you to participate in one of their classes for an informal chat We schedule the event We will make sure to find a time that is convenient for both you and the school and provide the online platform I m part of an educational institution How can I host a lecture? You can host lectures on a specific topic related to their research or a more general talk about "life as a scientist". T he first step to do it is to register on our database so that we can contact you and have the information we need to coordinate lectures in your Please note that registering does not involve committing to any immediate action! The next steps depend on whether a scientist can come in person or not, and the desired format: We d like to host a visiting scientist We d like to host a webinar We d like to virtually invite a scientist to a class We d like to host a visiting scientist We d like to host a webinar We d like to virtually invite a scientist to a class We contact you If a scientist is visiting your city town, we will email you asking if you would like to host them during their stay, and send you all the relevant information We schedule the lecture If you agree to host them, we work out the day and time of the lecture with both parts and put you in contact with the visiting scientist You host the scientist The visiting scientist comes to your institution in person to give a lecture on the agreed topic and for the agreed Make sure you invite your students! Visit our catalogue Available webinars are listed in our webinar catalogue . In the description of each webinar you ll find the languages and recommended age for it and a link to the scientist s profile Request a webinar You can use this form or email us to request one or more webinars from our catalogue . Please note that small adjustments can be made based on your needs We schedule it We will find a time that is convenient for you and the speaker and arrange the webinar Host the webinar We can provide the online platform, moderate the webinar and provide You only need to invite your students! Contact us You can email us to request the visit of a scientist, telling us the topic you re interested in, the age of the students and when you would like the scientist to You can also choose from our scientists page ! We find a scientist We will send you the relevant information about the scientist(s) we found for your class - including the link to their online profile if they have one - and wait for your approval They your class During the normal hours of your class and without you scheduling any special lecture, a scientist can attend yous class and be available for a chat with your students or to answer questions from them! Home Posted on March , by wabson One of the consequences of the pandemic is that in the future a lot more people will start to work from However more concerning right now is that a large numbers of people who have been used to going into the office the majority or entirety of the time have been asked to change their behaviour quite suddenly, to a model that they<U+0092>re not that familiar I<U+0092>m lucky to have worked across a number of teams at Alfresco where working from home has been helpful in many ways over the last few years to me personally, but I<U+0092>m also aware that there are quite a few So I put together this list to share with colleagues, having definitely exhibited the opposite behaviour of each of these at different times in the Try to keep a normal Although these are not normal times trying to keep to a rough schedule each day will help you manage the predictable and the unpredictable things Your mother was Don<U+0092>t forget to shower, do your hair, brush your teeth and dress properly at the start of each Have a defined and tidy work area where you can work from while you are at Move around if you need to, but try to sit up, lying on the sofa or bed will not end well Not everyone has space for a desk or a good solid table to work Use your imagination, an ironing board can be adjusted to the perfect height as needed and moved around Take regular breaks, especially for lunch, away from your Do something useful like put some washing on in the background, reducing the technical debt of your laundry pile will make you feel better and will only take a few minutes each Drink plenty of water and eat well, avoid processed food if you can Have a clear for work activities, as you would if you were in the Remember to schedule time to spend with friends and family (remotely as needed), or join a meetup or other activity remotely after work ends (thanks, Roberto ). Take care of your Consider joining remote meetings (we use Zoom ) a few minutes early, to have some time for unstructured and conversations before the agenda kicks Get regular Although most gyms, health clubs, etc are closed and many organised events such as Parkrun are suspended , it is still recommended in government advice that exercising outside is fine and indeed necessary for maintaining your health and wellbeing Keep with events and news but don<U+0092>t get hooked on watching rolling TV news or scrolling through social media, it will not make you feel better Do something small to improve your local Say hello to a stranger, ask the person in the shop how they are If you have conquered all the above, consider helping others in your communities or friendship circles who may be struggling with working remotely or feeling Many charities are seeking help in this area right now for themselves and their service users, and other groups such as the Marble Arch Partnership who we , by wabson Hot on the heels of the Alfresco Enterprise release this week, the Share Extras team have been busy pushing out an updated version of the Media Viewers , which provides support for viewing documents, audio, video and code directly within the web browser in place of the standard Share A key part of the release involved fixing up a few issues and adding additional support for the new document library views in such as the Filmstrip But users of any recent version of Alfresco should be able to benefit from some new features <U+0096> such as a new Present Mode for PowerPoint and ODP files <U+0096> and developers are also able to customize the toolbar using extensibility The full list of features is available from the releases page on the GitHub But what<U+0092>s also significant is that this is the first major release we<U+0092>ve completed for a Share Extras since we completed the migration to GitHub The new process ensures that the release is tagged in the repo, and has binary artifacts available from GitHub and from our new Maven repo (I<U+0092>m indebted to Gab Columbro for this, who helped to set it up). I<U+0092>ll be at Alfresco Summit this year in Barcelona talking about what was involved in the migration, both from a project management and from a technical standpoint in my talk Lessons Learned from Share Extras . You can catch me in Boston too, and at both conferences you<U+0092>re welcome to book a time to chat about Alfresco Integrations, Share Extras or in general at the Alfresco Experts Posted in Share Extras Changes to Transformers configuration in Alfresco Posted on July 9, by wabson If like me you have configured some custom transformers against the Alfresco repository in order to convert from one file type to another, you<U+0092>ll need to be aware of some changes that have been made in the codeline currently available in the HEAD branch in SVN and in the latest nightly builds . The major change is that the mimetype mappings which were previously defined via the Spring bean definitions have now moved to repository This has the benefit that the Spring configuration is much simpler and sys admins can more easily change which transformers are used for specific transforms, as well as the priority assigned to Today I added some default properties to the on Share Extras, which you may find useful as a guide to converting over any custom transformer Previously in the project, the transformer mimetype mappings were defined on the transformers<U+0092> Spring beans via the explicitTransformations Here is an <bean id="transformer.ffmpeg.flv" ... <property name="explicitTransformations" <list <bean class="org.alfresco.repo.content.transform.ExplictTransformationDetails" <property name="sourceMimetype" <value video mpeg< value < property <property name="targetMimetype" <value video x-flv< value < property < bean ... < list < property ... < bean This configuration configures this a transformer with the bean ID , which is capable of converting an file to Flash Video format (note that the transformation itself is performed by a separate worker bean since Alfresco , and that whilst not generally recommended, the explicitTransformation list can also be applied to that bean). In onwards the explicitTransformation property is no longer used, so we must define the following repository properties in addition to the Spring # Define a default priority for this transformer =50 # List the transformations that are supported =true =50 ... It is important to get the format of the properties right, with a prefix of followed by the Spring bean ID of the transformer ( in this case), followed by the suffixes First we define a numerical priority for this transformer, then each supported transformation must be listed separately, one on each line, with the source and target mimetypes identified by their default file extensions, which can be obtained from the mimetypes web script, http: localhost:8080 alfresco service mimetypes . As per Alan<U+0092>s advice on this related JIRA ticket , you can simply add the properties to your installation<U+0092>s , and they will take effect immediately after a restart, but if your transformer config is packaged up in an then you probably want to ship these properties with it, otherwise the transformer will be automatically configured to transform any mimetype into all others defined in the system (see this issue if you want to understand the consequences of this). For the project I utilised the ability of Alfresco Subsystems to pull in extended configuration properties placed on the classpath under alfresco extension subsystems . In this case I used the Transformers subsystem but perhaps thirdParty is also applicable for this, or you could even define your own custom subsystem! I added the properties in a new file config alfresco extension subsystems Transformers default default org_sharextras_media-viewers.properties in my project with the above contents ( source ). The config prefix is part of the standard project source layout and is removed from the classpath of the assets at build time, and the slightly obtuse file name ensures that different will not clash with each other if they both add additional properties (the file name can be anything, so long as it ends with the Normally you would remove the explicitTransformations properties from the Spring configuration with these applied, in order to supress the warnings that are now output in the logs, but I made the decision to leave it in, in order to preserve with and Thanks to the contributors davidyg and touchvignesh who reported these issues with the ! The updated code is in the master branch on Github or you can grab a JAR file containing the latest code to try it out Posted in Share Extras Media Viewers Released! Posted on February 1, by wabson If you<U+0092>ve been following the recent activity on Share Extras you<U+0092>ll notice that most of the work for the last few weeks has been going into the Media Viewers project and in particular the <U+0091>PdfJs<U+0092> based viewer which it If you<U+0092>re not familiar with the underlying project then you should know that it provides a means of direct rendering of PDF content items using HTML5 and JavaScript in the web browser, with no requirement from additional plugins such as Combined with the ability of the Alfresco repository to transform just about any standard document into PDF format, we think this provides a compelling reason to try the Media Viewer if you have not done so An initial version of the PdfJs viewer shipped in the Media Viewers release for Alfresco 4, and version which we<U+0092>re releasing today builds on that with support for Alfresco while also maintaining backwards compatible with the and Alfresco product There<U+0092>s so much in this release that it felt like much more than a release and seemed much more You can read on for more details of these exciting new capabilities, or go straight to the download, installation and configuration instructions to try it out Easy Configuration The first thing you<U+0092>ll notice when enabling the using Share<U+0092>s Module Deployment console is that additional modules have been added, which provide the configuration needed to bind the viewer into the document details Unless you want a specific custom configuration, you can just enable the new PdfJs Configuration module (in addition to the existing PdfJs Viewer module), click Apply Changes and you should see PDF documents will now use the new You no longer need to edit your file although if you<U+0092>ve made changes there they will continue to be Persistent View Settings Can<U+0092>t see the text clearly? You can use the zoom controls in the viewer to zoom in, our out if you want to see Or pick a preset from the and the zoom will be The next time you come back to the document, these settings <U+0096> plus the page number you were on <U+0096> will be Powerful Search Use the Search button in the toolbar or Ctrl+F (Cmd+F on MacOS) to search through the document contents for a particular item of You can easily step through the matches one by one, or highlight all matches When you<U+0092>ve found what you<U+0092>re after, you can copy the relevant text to the clipboard in order to include it somewhere else, for example in an The feature I like the most will make you wonder how you lived without it before, if you<U+0092>ve ever searched for a document in Alfresco and then struggled to find the reference to that term in the document Now, the viewer detects that you have clicked through from the search page, and automatically searches for and highlights the first match of that Just hit Enter to continue through any further matches, or Escape to close the search Link to Document The Link button in the toolbar generates a link to the document, or even to a specific page in the document, that you can send to If you want them to review Slide in your presentation then simply send them straight Improved Sidebar You can click the button on the left of the toolbar to toggle the side bar on and The side bar shows a thumbnail view of all pages in the document by default and can also show an outline of the document structure if available in the Presentation Mode At DevCon last November Jared neatly showed how you can use the the new Google Docs integration to deliver a presentation directly from your web browser using Google Drive<U+0092>s presentation mode, but with the PdfJs viewer you can now do the same thing directly from the Document Details Just click Ctrl+Enter (or Cmd+Enter on MacOS) to go , then use the left and right arrow keys to move between your slides (the arrow keys will also work in the normal Document Details view). Document Viewer Dashlet Just like Site Admins can use the Wiki dashlet to add a selected page to a site dashboard, the Document View dashlet supplied with the allows you to display any chosen document on the The dashlet works well with the PdfJs viewer, but will also work with the others supplied by the or the base viewers supplied with Share (yes, that includes the Flash document viewer, if you really want). PDFs Viewing PDFs is no longer a problem with the PdfJs You will be promoted for the password required to open the file and once supplied the viewer will work as Lots More Of course there are many other improvements that you can<U+0092>t see directly, but that you will benefit Peter has been working tirelessly to keep the version of the library , ensuring that we stay up to date with the improvements in performance and compatibility that the latest versions now We have also improved the performance of page rendering within the dashlet code itself, with improved lazy rendering of all page and thumbnail And of course PdfJs is not the only viewer in the The audio and video players are still supplied, the Embed viewer offers a compelling alternative for IE users not on IE who have the Adobe Reader or another PDF plugin installed and the Prettify viewer is great at syntax highlighting any code stored in Feedback Like all Share Extras , we welcome constructive feedback to help us to deliver the next version of Media Please use the Issues section on the project to report specific technical issues or ideas for enhancements, or general feedback can be left as comments Posted in Alfresco , Share Extras Media Viewers and Quick Share Posted on December 4, by wabson Peter helpfully put together a summary of a couple of the many different content viewers that are now provided by the Media Viewers His blog post is well worth checking out if you<U+0092>re not familiar with the Embed and PdfJs viewers, or if you have content types that you have problems previewing in Share He also pointed out something that may be obvious to some of you, but it had not occurred to me! When you add a new plugin to Alfresco<U+0092>s web preview component <U+0096> as this does <U+0096> then that is also available on the Quick Share If you<U+0092>re not familiar with Quick Share it is a great new feature originally in Cloud and now in Community , providing public sharing of documents via a short URL, which can be easily used by clicking the Share action directly above the document The result is pretty powerful, since using an iFrame you can easily add those embedded documents to an intranet page or public web page <U+0096> or just link to the items direct as Peter has done in his In fact Sergio Buitrago and I worked on this implementing this very thing as a WordPress plugin at the Berlin DevCon Hackathon last month! Latest Changes in PdfJs Viewer It<U+0092>s worth mentioning that you can try out the features Peter mentions by grabbing the project<U+0092>s latest source from In particular, here are two new features that are hot off the press in the PdfJs viewer: Perform a search in Share and click through to a PDF file or office You should see that the search function is automatically invoked for the term you searched for in the previous page, and highlights the first If you are using the latest available Firefox or Chrome browsers, you can enter mode by pressing Ctrl+F on the Now you can deliver PowerPoint presentations directly from Share itself! We are still in the process of finalising the release of the Media Viewers , so if you have feedback please file an issue on the Share Extras project site . talk on the and Maven SDK was a highlight as much for the content as for Gab<U+0092>s style, although you<U+0092>ll want to do some background reading on Maven and how it differs from more traditional been up to over the last year (or six months in my case), and Nathan<U+0092>s overview of PDF Toolkit and the latest new features, based on the work he<U+0092>s done recently building on Jared<U+0092>s earlier If you<U+0092>re interested in integrating Share with external systems and working with PDF content you<U+0092>ll find both sessions really Overall what stood out this year for me was the diversity of sessions available, not only in terms of topics but in their formats as There were less of the type of sessions and more richer interactive I experimented with a local Git repo
