Posted in Alfresco | Tagged Alfresco , DevCon CMIS support in LibreOffice Experimental Features Posted on November 1, by wabson Since I upgraded the LibreOffice installation on my Macbook to version , I<U+0092>ve been playing around with the CMIS integration built into this This is currently an experimental LibreOffice feature, which means you should not use this against a production The integration allows LibreOffice to connect to a remote Alfresco server in order to open and save This is a feature Microsoft Office has had for a long time, although limited to servers (including Alfresco, via our SharePoint protocol support !). Now you can do the same thing with LibreOffice, via the magic of The first thing to do is to enable LibreOffice<U+0092>s experimental features within the Preferences After you<U+0092>ve confirmed that change, you can open a file stored in Alfresco using the standard Open When the file browser loads, you should notice a small button next to the location menu labelled with an ellipsis (<U+0085>). Clicking that button allows you to add a LibreOffice supports a range of server types, including the CMIS AtomPub service provided by First you must enter a name for the server <U+0096> I entered <U+0091>Alfresco<U+0092> <U+0096> and select the server If you do not see CMIS (Atom Binding) in the list then check to ensure that you have LibreOffice + and that you have enabled Experimental The binding URL for Alfresco will be something like http: localhost:8080 alfresco cmisatom if you are running a local I found that if I used the legacy CMIS URL below alfresco service (or the short form alfresco s ) then document saves did not work, but the newer URL worked Next is the slightly tricky part, entering the CMIS repository Your Alfresco instance will only expose one repository, but other CMIS providers provide others, and so you need to enter Hitting the repository binding URL directly will give you the ID, but unfortunately the document MIME type returned means it does not open directly in a web You could save the response to disk and then use a text editor to view its contents, but I found it easier to use curl at the command line, together with curl admin:admin http: localhost:8080 alfresco cmisatom | less In the response, do a search for the string repositoryId and within that element you should see a GUID value which you can copy and paste into the dialogue in The last item you need to enter is the username that will be used to access Alfresco (you will enter the password later). You should now have the full set of information needed to add the Click OK, and it should be added to the side panel on the left of the Open You can navigate through the folders below the repository<U+0092>s Company Home space, and open any compatible I used the Word documents located under Sites swsdp documentLibrary Meeting Notes, which opened You can make any modifications, hit Save and the content will be automatically saved back into I also tried creating a new document from the New menu, and was able to save the document back to a folder Alfresco via the Save As I found I needed to set the correct MIME type for new documents back in Alfresco Share to get previews to work, but this could easily be done using a All in all not bad for an experimental feature, and it will be interesting to see if this makes it into LibreOffice for Posted in Alfresco | Tagged Alfresco , atompub , cmis , libreoffice New Notice Dashlet and Improvements for Developers Posted on October , by wabson Following hot on the heels of the release from last week, it<U+0092>s great to see going out this week with another bunch of improvements before DevCon . I<U+0092>ve been able to help get a few more changes into the this release, which provide a new dashlet and several improvements for Notice Dashlet This dashlet may already be familiar to some of you who have used the available from Share The Notice Dashlet allows site managers to add a custom notice that will be displayed to all site members, and allows this to be done directly from the dashlet Now you no longer need to create a wiki page just to display some basic text on the dashboard! New Bubbling event for dashlet resize notifications If you<U+0092>ve developed any complex dashlets to render maps or other graphics, you<U+0092>ll appreciate that it<U+0092>s important to know the vertical height of the dashlet when you render your That is easy to get via the Dom or using YUI2<U+0092>s () function, but what if the user resizes the dashlet? Now the resizer module can notify your listeners via the new Bubbling event dashletResizeEnd . This is fired when the resizing has been completed and passes a number of parameters in the event arguments, including the new height of the dashlet, the dashlet element and component IDs and the Dom element representing the To subscribe to the event, simply define a new custom function in your dashlet class prototype and bind it to the event in the dashlet class constructor, ("dashletResizeEnd", , this) In your custom function you can then take any further action which is necessary, informing a map instance that the element bounds have More options for Data List actions The ability to add custom UI actions to Share<U+0092>s Document Library is well documented and the site has a number of extensions which utilize this But did you know the same thing can be done for data list items? Until now the number of actions that can be displayed in the UI has been effectively capped at But now you can easily add new actions of your own there Thanks to the work done by Dave Draper these definitions can easily be inserted into the application by using an extensibility module to customize the and As an example, the following code could be used to add the Sample Datalist Action provided by Share Extras to your datalist items, as part of an extensibility if (model.widgets) for (var i = 0 i < i++) var widget = [i] if (widget.id == "DataGrid") These two lines only needed if you want to show the action in the actions cell, otherwise a More actions menu will be created to display widget.options.splitActionsAt = 4 widget.options.actionsColumnWidth = splitActionsAt + 5 Add the action definition - this will be ( id: "onActionSample", Change to match your handler function name type: "action-link", permission: "", href: "", label: "actions.datalist.mycustom" Change to match your custom label in ) If you have attempted to customize the existing Edit and Create data list actions with your own custom form configuration, then you may also appreciate the ability to increase the width of the modal dialogs used here, which previously were Better handling of missing custom previewers This will mainly be of interest to developers and administrators working with custom viewers in the web preview component, such as the viewer in Share Extras<U+0092>s Media Viewers , and is a topic which I<U+0092>ll be talking about in San Jose next Previously, if the files implementing the viewer were unavailable for some reason then an error would be thrown in the With this change the component now logs that the viewer class could not be found, and this will also be printed on the screen if no other viewers can be Posted in Alfresco Creating SSL certificates for Solr Posted on August , by wabson Since the default SSL certificates that ship with Alfresco<U+0092>s Solr integration expired the other week I<U+0092>ve been having to fix up my local development installs that I<U+0092>d previously configured with The instructions on the wiki are pretty comprehensive, and together with the text file provided in the Solr integration package provide all the info you need to understand the process of creating your own keys and certificates for local After I stepped through the complete procedure documented there, with some slight modifications to avoid the interactive prompting, I found I had a set of commands which I could use in order to repeatedly a set of keys inside each installation directory on my The first section in the following listing could be placed inside your file, and this is recommended to ensure that the password values you choose to use are not captured in your command history or in your The commands after that should be used repeatedly against each Alfresco installation you wish to generate keys and certificates # The subject name of the key used to sign the certificates REPO_SUBJECT_NAME=" C=GB ST=UK L=Maidenhead O=Alfresco Software OU=Unknown CN=Alfresco Repository" # The repository server certificate subject name, as specified in tomcat conf tomcat-users.xml with roles="repository" REPO_CERT_DNAME="CN=Alfresco Repository, OU=Unknown, O=Alfresco Software , L=Maidenhead, ST=UK, C=GB" # The SOLR client certificate subject name, as specified in tomcat conf tomcat-users.xml with roles="repoclient" SOLR_CLIENT_CERT_DNAME="CN=Alfresco Repository Client, OU=Unknown, O=Alfresco Software , L=Maidenhead, ST=UK, C=GB" # The number of days before the certificate expires CERTIFICATE_VALIDITY=36525 # Keystore password KEYSTORE_PASSWORD=custompassword BROWSER_KEYSTORE_PASSWORD=alfresco openssl genrsa pass:$KEYSTORE_PASSWORD openssl req pass:$KEYSTORE_PASSWORD "$REPO_SUBJECT_NAME" pass:$KEYSTORE_PASSWORD # Generate Alfresco Repository SSL keystores keytool ssl.repo RSA JCEKS "$REPO_CERT_DNAME" "$KEYSTORE_PASSWORD" "$KEYSTORE_PASSWORD" keytool ssl.repo JCEKS "$KEYSTORE_PASSWORD" openssl x509 "$CERTIFICATE_VALIDITY" pass:$KEYSTORE_PASSWORD keytool alfresco.ca JCEKS $KEYSTORE_PASSWORD keytool ssl.repo JCEKS $KEYSTORE_PASSWORD keytool $KEYSTORE_PASSWORD JCEKS ssl.repo $KEYSTORE_PASSWORD pkcs12 $BROWSER_KEYSTORE_PASSWORD repo $BROWSER_KEYSTORE_PASSWORD keytool JCEKS $KEYSTORE_PASSWORD # Generate Alfresco Solr SSL keystores keytool ssl.repo.client RSA JCEKS $KEYSTORE_PASSWORD "$KEYSTORE_PASSWORD" "$SOLR_CLIENT_CERT_DNAME" keytool ssl.repo.client JCEKS $KEYSTORE_PASSWORD openssl x509 "$CERTIFICATE_VALIDITY" pass:$KEYSTORE_PASSWORD keytool alfresco.ca JCEKS $KEYSTORE_PASSWORD keytool ssl.repo.client JCEKS $KEYSTORE_PASSWORD keytool alfresco.ca JCEKS $KEYSTORE_PASSWORD # Copy files cp data keystore cp solr workspace-SpacesStore conf cp solr archive-SpacesStore conf # Remove temporary files rm Note that this will not update the Alfresco and Solr configuration with the password you choose for the keystores <U+0096> you must do this separately in your and in the properties file associated with each Solr core, as detailed in the Solr installation Lastly, this procedure should not be used in any or production instances, it is intended to be used in development environments Posted in Alfresco | Tagged Alfresco , solr , ssl Post navigation <U+2190> Older posts Archives Model Green and Healthy Housing Children and Youth Publications Data Clearinghouse & Housing Resources Flood Hazard + Housing Practitioner Information Network The Shimberg Center for Housing Studies was established at the University of Florida in to promote safe, decent and affordable housing and related community development throughout the state of News Highlights Data: Eviction and Foreclosure Filings Data for Florida Counties 5 17 2021 The Shimberg Center s data application now includes eviction and foreclosure filing counts in Florida county and circuit The evictions data was recently featured in Locked Out , an Orlando Sentinel series on the impacts of evictions on Florida The database tracks evictions and foreclosures filed across the state from January to December We plan to update the filing records Users can view monthly eviction and foreclosure totals by county, the rate of evictions and foreclosures per 1,000 households, and the change in these figures between and Across Florida counties, eviction filings were actually lower compared to the previous year, as Florida Governor Ron DeSantis implemented a statewide moratorium halting the entire Filings started to rise in August and September as the moratorium conditions became more narrowly A specific cause of nonpayment was required, and landlords could still file an eviction, with the final action on In September, the state s moratorium was replaced by the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) moratorium, which has been extended through June This moratorium only protects rental eviction and requires that tenants declare a related job or income In most counties, eviction filings ticked up steadily throughout the rest of The evictions and foreclosures database is part of the Florida Housing Data Clearinghouse s larger : Workforce & Housing Indicators resource intended to paint the broader picture of s myriad ripple effects on housing and the The resource tracks monthly unemployment rates and employment by industry throughout to identify the Research Brief: Shaping Healthy Affordable Housing through Policy, Design, Place 16 2020 New research from the Shimberg Center and University of Illinois looks at the role of state policy in promoting healthy living environments in homes funded by the Low Income Housing Tax Credit (LIHTC). The researchers studied a wide array of health factors including healthy neighborhood environments, energy efficiency, indoor air quality, noise, green building materials, and We<U+0092>re hiring! Tenured tenure-track faculty position available 9 2020 The Shimberg Center in the Rinker, School of Construction Management invites applications for one tenured or faculty position in housing studies beginning in the fall of Full job description here apply here . Florida Unemployment at ,000 in October 30 2020 The number of unemployed workers in Florida rose from ,000 in January to 1,304,000 in May, then fell to ,000 in October, according to a new fact sheet, and Unemployment in Florida: October Update . In all, the state added ,000 unemployed workers between January and Other key findings: The number of jobs lost was greatest in , Broward, and Orange Unemployment in Osceola County peaked at % in May before falling to % in Jobs in the leisure and hospitality industry were hardest hit by See employment changes for all counties and industries with the : Workforce & Housing Indicators data tool . For more information about the impacts of on housing and the economy in Florida, see our & Housing Resources page . CODY Virtual Reality Tool Allows Persons with Parkinson<U+0092>s Disease to Experience Home Modifications 6 21 2020 The Shimberg Center and partners launched the CODY (Co-Design for You) Virtual Reality tool to help persons with Parkinson s Disease and other movement difficulties to redesign interior home features to best fit their The CODY tool allows the user to test different safety options without having to move items around Sherry Ahrentzen (Shimberg Center), Ravi Srinivasan (M.E. Rinker, School of Construction Management) and Shabboo Valipoor (Department of Interior Design) led this interdisciplinary study that includes researchers from College of Medicine, Department of Occupational Therapy, College of Journalism and Communications, and College of the Arts and Department of Learn more and watch a video on the project here . Shimberg Center launches resource, data pages 4 10 2020 Today the Shimberg Center launched two new Web pages with information about and housing in : Workforce and Housing Indicators provides data on housing cost burdens, older populations, children<U+0092>s access to Internet and health insurance, worker counts in service industries, and subsidized housing sites eligible for new tenant protections under the federal CARES & Housing Resources describes the data and provides links to relevant news articles and housing resources from our Check back frequently for updates to both pages, and send us suggestions or custom data requests to Report: Nearly ,000 Florida students identified as homeless amid housing shortage, hurricane 16 2019 Students Experiencing Homelessness in Florida: Updates and Solutions finds that in the school year, ,873 students in Florida schools were identified as homeless<U+0096>nearly triple the number from ten years Of these, ,721 students were made homeless by hurricanes, including ,968 students who moved from Puerto Rico to Florida after Hurricane The Shimberg Center and Miami Homes for All this new report with support from JPMorgan Chase and See also fact sheets on student homelessness , an interactive map of Florida schools and homeless student counts, and more . Research Brief: Older households, renters make up most of Florida<U+0092>s recent The affordable rental housing gap 11 2019 A new research brief summarizes findings on statewide housing trends from the Rental Market Study . The Center also released briefs on regional rental housing trends in South Florida , Northeast Florida , the Orlando area , and the Tampa Bay area . In addition to documenting the shortage of affordable rental housing statewide, the briefs show that most of the state<U+0092>s growth since has come from age + homeowners and renters of all ages, while the state has been losing younger Tweets by ShimbergCenter Explore our Data Clearinghouse College of Design, Construction & Planning Rinker, School of Construction Management Box Gainesville, FL Tel: (352) Fax: (352) About Contact Site Map

Snowfox Project This project is retired due to MCU complexity and increasingly better vendor provided HALs and Snowfox License Support Github Blog Sponsors Strong Compile Time Checks Codebase compiled with , , and . C++17 Support Enjoy =c++17 on your Minimal Target Specific Code Codebase can be compiled for both host and Minimal Conditional Compilation No need to suffer in #ifdef hell . Judicious Usage of Macros There are no macros . CMake Build System Build from CLI or use any IDE . No dynamic memory allocation after startup Dynamic memory allocation on embedded systems comes with a couple of risks (system might run , malloc new might take a unexpected long time due to running a heap defragmentation algorithm). Snowfox eliminates those risks by only allocating dynamic memory during the startup phase . What? Snowfox is a embedded software framework consisting of Hardware Abstraction Layer IO driver support for various sensors, actuators and communication controllers Industrial communication stacks written in C++ subjected to rigorous unit and integration tests . Why #1? The application of OO principles such as SOLID leads to a clean code base and minimizes coupling between This enables the application of Test Driven Development which gives developers instantenous feedback on their code therefore eliminating tedious integration and bug fixing sessions typical for Why #2? In his book Refactoring: Improving the Design of Existing Code Martin Fowler frankly states that <U+0093>Any fool can write code that a computer can Good programmers write code that humans can <U+0094> This project aims to do just that for the embedded You are kindly invited to browse the code and form your own opinion about how well the code is adhering to our Complete codebase compilable for AVR, RISCV and All supported MCU configurations as well as all examples are build on every Code functionality is verified with unit tests which are executed on every High code quality is maintained through the whole Copyright <U+00A9> LXRobotics All rights GDPR Imprint

STG Interactive was initially created to develop Frogans, a new medium for publishing content and services on the Internet . In , STG Interactive founded the Organization for the Promotion, Protection and Progress of Frogans Technology (OP3FT) . Until the end of , STG Interactive was the FCR Operator, the entity responsible for the technical and commercial operation of the Frogans Core Registry (FCR) . Introduction | TroopJS Docs Contrib API Docs getting started Getting Started Introduction Installation Kick Start Core Concepts Compose Component Events Widget Data TroopJS is a minimalist framework for building scalable javascript It s intrinsically modular, declarative, interoperable and TroopJS is best for complex web pages that assembles massive amount of applications that are meant to be compatible with different building web pages that you intend to maintain for a long period of Why TroopJS Enterprise JavaScript applications are a ! As it scales, the more complex it becomes and before you know it, you re stuck with disorganized, fragile and unmaintainable TroopJS lets you avoid the madness through the following: Asynchronous by Promise A+ , lets you stay away from callback hell Component is enforced so as each component is rendered in isolation, addressing the complexity of large applications, coincident with the Web component concept Expresses behaviors in a declarative way, to help your code stay sane and maintainable Event is used for communication, because reactive beats proactive, components DO NOT reference other components, allowing your application to be interoperable via asynchronous Open ended implementation, it doesn t prescribe a particular rendering style or data model definition, so TroopJS components can be integrated seamlessly with any other libraries like jQuery plugins, template system, , rendering engine, controller, router, Dependencies There are a couple of wheels that we don t want to reinvent in TroopJS, so we are drawing the minimalist dependencies on a few standard compliant, libraries: poly Compatibility Despite being a modern JavaScript framework, all TroopJS bundle modules are fully compatible with all major Yep, all the way down to IE6 . TroopJS runs fast even on relatively less performant mobile web containers like web TroopJS runtime mainly tragets the browser Having said that, core+ modules can run perfectly on Node using an AMD loader like requireJS which will allow you to run TroopJS components on the with a different rendering Footprint The maximal (maxi.js) TroopJS bundle is currently at minified + Status TroopJS is still a young We re proud of what we ve achieved in v3 but we re hungry and ambitious for If you want to be part of its evolution, we d like to hear from Start by creating an issue Credits TroopJS will not be possible if not for the support provided by EF Learning Labs . It s main contributors at the moment are by and . To get a full list of contributors, please view this link . Find an error? Let us know <U+2192>

He also created the initial Cryptsy trading script, which was the foundation for this Jasper van Gelder Business Magician Jasper has a passion for bringing IT technology into With a current degree in Computer Science, he is currently doing his Master ICT in Business at Leiden During his employment in several high tech innovative IT companies, he saw a growing need of filling the gap between business problems and IT How we started In , Stefan wanted to try out Bitcoin mining and ordered a graphics card to do While waiting for his card, Stefan developed a script to trade on Cryptsy which was working so well, that when the card came in it was barely breaking even but the script already made 1 BTC in a few At this point, Stefan felt this script was worth improving and got into contact with From that moment on we, started to develop an optimized program written in C++ instead of a Python This was very successful - we passed the BTC mark in late In May, however, we saw a decline in our profits, so we started to develop a new algorithm and revamped the whole software After a lot of work this started to pay off and the profits started to go up We have discussed several times whether or not to start selling our In October , we finally decided to sell, but we both agreed that we had to do something about the user At that point the program was still running from a config file, which had attained an increasingly complex To solve this we started to develop a GUI which would generate the config file About 2 months later we put our GUI to the test and asked some of our friends if they wanted to try our This led to long sessions of feedback on how to improve our After some debate we decided to halt the sales of our trading software in march When we started with our sales in we had a hard time pricing our We knew it was performing well but it all depends on the markets and the available amount to trade We could did not want to create a commission based model because the only way to do this was by managing customers That was something we were trying to avoid because it is contradictory to the cryptocurrency ethos of decentralization but also would expose us to a lot of risk and trouble from This is the reason why we settled for a fixed fee subscription because at the time it seemed to be the best This has given our customers value for their money we noticed that on markets our customers weren t active on we gained more Upfront we did not think it would be such a big issue because the amount with what we traded was relatively However over the years our impact in the market had increased thanks to our customers but most importantly our So we decided we gained enough capital to continue our business in private and no longer accept new About urbansurgery - creating new urban fabrics One concern of urbansurgery is to consider how we can treat our neighbours ethically by crafting the physical city in such a way that it can be easily used by all of its people <U+0097> so that not only , adults with cars but also children, the elderly, the poor, the blind, the halt, and the lame can have freedom of movement and convenient access to all the good things that cities We can strive for no less if we imagine ourselves to be a just and ethical Political and economic freedom in the abstract mean little without any practical freedom of movement or Good urban design enables people to get around safely, efficiently, and in pleasant surroundings, creating value in a fairly direct and obvious Nevertheless, good urban design also creates value indirectly by enabling a city s people to create value and make it available to others through free At one level, we are concerned with the cities hardware at another level, we are concerned with the software <U+0097> with what people do in the As we shall see, the most important thing that people do in cities is exchange things <U+0097> goods, services, and money, but also ideas, beliefs, knowledge, and love <U+0097> with other Exchange depends on Moreover, proximity is business of At least it used to After World War II, and increasingly after , urban form fundamentally changed with the rise of the regional shopping mall, the large discount store, the franchise, the office ark, the motorways, the insular residential housing estate, and the functional segregation brought by zoning <U+0097> in short, Proximity and connectedness <U+0097> which were a matter of course in the re compact, intimately scaled city of the past <U+0097> have been replaced by fragmentation and separation, both in the expanding peripheries and, increasingly, in the decaying and "urban-renewaled" interiors of Exchange of goods, knowledge, and ideas is Television, radio, the Internet and email now provide an artificial proximity, but this is a pale imitation of the real proximity of a glance at the shop window and a visit to the We are not geographic An arrangement of urban space that facilitates exchange will not solve all urban Connectedness and proximity are, we believe, necessary conditions for a healthy economy, culture, and community, but they are not the only necessary conditions, and they are certainly not sufficient Nor do we entertain nostalgic yearnings for the supposed golden age before automobiles, expressways, television and We do, however, entertain a reasonable and practical hope that these and other features of contemporary culture can be integrated into a coherent framework that facilitates many kinds of exchange and preserves not just the sense of community but the fact of That is the guiding principle behind this new urban There is a lot at stake in this The intense creativity and democratisation that occurred in cities from the Middle Ages through the late industrial period were, we believe, associated with the physicality of those cities <U+0097> not just with the fact of concentration but with the how of it, with certain characteristics of scale and density and the way the parts The compact city of the old style is now valued, where it survives, mainly for its "historic " But it also was and is a highly efficient technology for fostering innovation, supporting diversity, and extending freedom while at the same time maintaining a stable base of historical consciousness, tradition, and social We don t want to dismiss the undeniable difficulties, dangers and injustices of life in the city, but it seems to me there was something about the way historic cities were assembled that brought people, things, and ideas together in a , continually spiralling cycle of exchanges that created In its essence, the city is a technology and a medium of In that case, have not advances in electronic communications made the city obsolete? Is not the old city of streets and stores and theatres and offices being supplanted by the new city of cable and dispersed workstations? We do not believe that the communitarian city of personal contact is obsolete, either economically or It used to be predicted that thirty or forty channels of television would keep people glued constantly to the However, since cable and satellite television became widespread, the use of parks, theatres, and recreation facilities has increased, not decreased, even in neighbourhoods where population has People still want to get out of the house and enjoy community life in the company of their It seems that the more we appreciate what electronics cannot give Corporations whose idea workers can now do their jobs in private offices, connected to their colleagues only by computer networks and telephones, have learned the importance of architectural features that encourage, even require, serendipitous social contact at strategically placed water coolers and lounges, which is where much of the real work gets cities and city neighbourhoods have certain essential capabilities that lie beyond the scope of other communications The advertising slogan notwithstanding, a telephone is useless if you want to reach out and touch someone, or (or ) contact is qualitatively different <U+0097> indeed, even quantitatively different, measured in terms of the bits of information exchanged <U+0097> from any existing or foreseeable form of electronic communication, including virtual In addition, it is contact that the city as a communications technology is designed to Neither a fulfilling personal life nor an advancing economic life can be detached from a healthy community There is a energy in the city that cannot be duplicated by other technologies, however powerful and brilliant and liberating they may The task before us is to regain and revivify so that we may make full use of this creative

van Opijnen Lab Welcome RESEARCH PEOPLE Publications JOBS SEQUENCING CORE Location Welcome RESEARCH PEOPLE Publications JOBS SEQUENCING CORE Location The van Opijnen Lab Our work The Lab The van Opijnen Lab VAN OPIJNEN LAB STATEMENT The van Opijnen Lab stands for a collaborative culture that embraces equity, diversity, and inclusion as a source of We reject systemic discrimination, exclusion or hatred that promotes a narrow, exclusionary vision for our . LATEST NEWS July - Summer is in full swing and we<U+0092>ve got something new for you to Bharathi Sundaresh got her first manuscript accepted at Trends in Molecular Medicine where she reports on host modulating strategies to control bacterial Stay tuned for the link to the article! May - The Boston Bacterial Meeting is arguably one of our favorite places to present our BBM will be on June & , and this year will be extra special with a on both days! On Thursday June @ , Federico Rosconi will present his work on strain dependent and evolvable , while on June @ Bharathi Sundaresh will present a new approach to uncover bacterial interactions with the host immune system and how we<U+0092>re using that to design novel host informed treatment Moreover, Suyen, Bimal and Juance will be presenting posters on their work! April - In collaboration with the labs of Vaughn Cooper (Pitt), Jason Rosch (St. Jude), Ralph Isberg (Tufts) and Eddie Geisinger (Northeastern) we have this incredible paper under review that shows how antibiotic persistence mutations present a risk during disease causing drug treatment failure in the immunocompromised host while simultaneously increasing the likelihood of AMR While its under review you can read the paper on bioRxiv 10.1101 2021.04.07.438861 and hopefully we<U+0092>ll see this work published soon! March - A lack of updates in the last couple of months doesn<U+0092>t mean nothing has happened, actually lots We<U+0092>ve had several rotation students pass through our Currently we<U+0092>re hosting two rotation students: Irem Ozkan and Jelena Momirov! People in the lab have started to receive their vaccinations, hooray! Multiple presentations were given including by Bharathi Sundaresh, Juance Ortiz and Suyen We<U+0092>re working on finishing up 3 massive research papers and a review, and we had two papers accepted: In Infection and Immunity as part of a collaboration with Amber Smith at the University of Tennessee, and In the Journal of Bacteriology as part of a collaboration with Eddie Geisinger at Northeastern So it<U+0092>s been a great start to a new year, we just can<U+0092>t wait to properly cellebrate all of November - If you<U+0092>re like us and you can<U+0092>t get enough of Transposon Insertion Sequencing (TIS), then we got another treat for you, in the form of a new Together with Henry Levin at the NIH we explored the development and implementation of and similar related approaches in all kinds of organisms including microbes and eukaryotes, we describe some of the most important pittfalls in TIS and how to overcome them and tried to give a detailed overview of existing analytical tools for TIS Go and enjoy it here at the Annual Review of Genetics . October - We published two new papers with our collaborators at the Gao and Burch lab<U+0092>s at The first describes a graphene based diagnostics device to detect host biomarkers in You can read about it here: mds3.10121 . The second paper describes the screening and validation for new peptide probes specific for colistin resistant Acinetobacter baumannii , which is a super important pathogen often causing hospital acquired infections due to This wonderful piece of work you can read here : acsinfecdis.0c00206 September - WOW! We just published another fantastic paper in Nature Communications . This time in collaboration with the labs from Eddie Geisinger at Northeastern University and Ralph Isberg at We map out antibiotic hypersensitivity signatures that predict functions of "dark matter", unannotated genes and new antibiotic synergies! You can find the paper by clicking on this September - We are incredibly excited about a new publication in Nature Communications , work that marries large scale experiments with some great computation performed by former graduate student Karen Zhu, grad Student Defne Surujon and postdoc Juance Moreover it includes critical collaborations with the Bento lab at BC and Ralph Isberg<U+0092>s lab at We present a new concept in biology by developing transcriptional entropy as a generalizable predictor of bacterial fitness, antibiotic sensitivity and as a quantitative predictor of a bacterium<U+0092>s MIC independent of strain, species and type of stress! You can read all about it here <U+0085>AND to give some insight into how we got here you can read our blogpost on the Nature Microbiology community site, on how we came up with this new idea by throwing rocks in the water for no good reason: https: go.nature.com 2QKnWZ4 July - Two new papers were accepted at Nature Communications and one at Annual Reviews in Genetics, stay tuned for updates on these cool pieces of work! However, if you can<U+0092>t wait you can find the bioRxiv links for the Nature papers on our publications July - It has been a little over years since the development of and related Together with those involved we wrote a review on a decade of advances in transposon insertion sequencing, which you can find in Nature Reviews Genetics . June - Our latest paper, in collaboration with the Isberg lab at Tufts, developing a microfluidics strategy that mimics Yersinia growing in tissue, its nitric oxide induced social behavior, and its interactions with macrophages is published at eLife , check it out: doi: eLife.58106 . May - Bacterial make you question the species definition, it affects the way bacteria become resistant against antibiotics, it can affect their virulence or vaccine You can read about all this and more in our and other chapters in this NEW and FREE! PanGenome book edited by Herv<e9> Tettelin & Duccio May - Recently we developed (see news from December), now we used the droplet technology from that publication to help Stacie Clark at the Isberg lab at TUFTS to develop a strategy that mimics Yersinia growing in tissue, its nitric oxide induced social behavior, and its interactions with The manuscript is currently under review, but you can already explore the preprint at bioRxiv . March - In collaboration with the labs of Ralph Isberg at Tufts and Eddie Geisinger at Northeastern we have a great new paper under We performed on Acinetobacter baumannii in the presence of different antibiotics, leading to detailed new insights into how different antibiotics affect and kill bacteria and new synergistic antibiotic combinations to battle them! You can already read the paper here on bioRxiv ! February - Juance Ortiz is a first author on a new paper just accepted in Biosensors and Bioelectronics ! Functionalize graphene with some of our special selected peptides, and there you have it, a device that fits on the tip of your finger and senses antibiotic resistant bacteria at a single cell level! Hello Diagnostics for the Future! Read all about our work with the Burch and Gao labs here! The van Opijnen Lab practices microbial systems biology which basically means that we try to understand a bacterium as a complete So instead of carefully studying the organism one component at the time we build networks of all the genetic elements that drive a bacterium s Thereby we rapidly develop a real good understanding of how a bacterium does its thing, for instance trigger Our work We mainly focus on pathogenic bacteria and apply a combination of robotics, next generation sequencing and computational biology to discover what makes them Our work We mainly focus on pathogenic bacteria and apply a combination of robotics, next generation sequencing and computational biology to discover what makes them The van Opijnen Lab focuses on projects to determine how bacteria trigger disease on a level and scale, we elucidate the fine inner workings of antibiotics and we develop new tools and screens to identify novel antimicrobial More research The Lab The Lab Tim van opijnen Principal Investigator van Opijnen received his Masters in evolutionary genetics from the University of Amsterdam, and as a graduate student he worked on the evolution of HIV at the Medical School of the University of As a postdoctoral fellow in the lab of Andrew Camilli at Tufts University in Boston his interests shifted to bacterial pathogens and systems In January he started his own lab on Microbial Systems Biology at Boston The workers Postdocs & Grad students Check out the PEOPLE for more information on who s who in the If you are interested in joining the lab as a postdoc, grad student or technician, the JOBS page for possible The Rookies Undergraduates We house a large flock of undergraduate students on the computational and side of the Each undergraduate works in close collaboration with a postdoc or graduate If you are interested in joining the lab as an undergraduate student please send an inquiry email including your CV to van A production of Boston College Top The Xapian Project Welcome to the Xapian project Xapian is an Open Source Search Engine Library, released under the GPL v2+ . It s written in C++ , with bindings to allow use from Perl , Python 2 , Python 3 , PHP 5 , PHP 7 , Java , Tcl , C# , Ruby , Lua , Erlang , and R (so far!) Xapian is a highly adaptable toolkit which allows developers to easily add advanced indexing and search facilities to their own It has support for several families of weighting models and also supports a rich set of boolean query If you re after a packaged search engine for your website, you should take a look at Omega : an application we supply built upon Unlike most other website search solutions, Xapian s versatility allows you to extend Omega to meet your needs as they The latest stable version is , released on The latest old stable version is , released on home features history mailing lists docs current users sponsors commercial support download bleeding edge bugs contact us search this website
